<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- German software company Logware has come to the
Middle East, opening its first offshore venture in Dubai of the
United Arab Emirates (UAE) with Shafeen International as the
company's exclusive distributor for the Middle East and North
African market.
</P>
<P>
Ulf Grupe, Logware Middle East operations manager, said the
company hoped to have 500 installed systems in the Middle East by
next year, with the UAE and Saudi Arabia as the major markets for
its IT solutions aimed at retail businesses.
</P>
<P>
"The Middle East is a fast-growing market and we are confident
that we can handle the requirements for IT solutions in retail
businesses here," Grupe was quoted Sunday by the local media as
saying.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- A new 5-star hotel is under construction in the
emirate of Fujairah in the northeast of the United Arab Emirates
(UAE), Saeed bin Saeed Al Sharqi, chairman of the Fujairah Tourism
Bureau, said at a tourism meeting held Sunday in the emirate.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, he also met representatives of more than 15
Russian travel agencies and discussed with them means of attracting
more Russian tourists to the emirate, reported the official WAM
news agency on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"We want to introduce Fujairah to tourist representatives and
travel agencies in Russia to bring groups of tourists to visit
Fujairah," said Al Sharqi, adding that efforts are being made to
make Fujairah one of the important tourism destinations in the UAE.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The South Korean Power-Generating Authority (PGA) has
entered the tender for building a power-generating station in
northern Cairo according to the BOT system.
</P>
<P>
The PGA offer involves 600 million U.S. dollars for launching
the station, Al-Hayat daily reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's investments in Egypt did not exceed 130 million U.
S. dollars at present as they started a short time ago. And the
investment will hit 1 billion dollars in 2002, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will sign documents of four joint projects in the
areas of weaving, transport, communications and ship-building. The
deals involve 620 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) states are
collectively studying the possibility of banning the import of
Firestone tyres due to global doubts over their technical
specifications after 63 deaths in accidents involving the tyre in
the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Last Wednesday, Saudi Arabia moved ahead of other GCC countries
by banning the import of Firestone tyres as well as new and used
vehicles fitted with them, local media reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Firestone's parent company, the Japanese group Bridgestone, was
forced to recall 6.5 million U.S.-made Firestone tyres earlier this

month. They were said to burst or peel off at speeds of 100 or 120
kilometers per hour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000828.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Hopes Somalia's Positive Steps Lead to End of Anarchy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Egypt on Monday expressed hope the
positive steps taken recently by the Somali people will help the
country usher in a new age that will realize national
reconciliation and end of anarchy.
</P>
<P>
A statement released by the Foreign Ministry said that Egypt
will always support the Somali people and their efforts to
establish a central government and restore unity of the country.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has been closely watching the developments of the Somali
national reconciliation conference held in Djibouti, the statement
said, urging the Somalis to discard differences and close ranks for
reuniting the country.
</P>
<P>
Somalia has been in division since 1991 when the former
president, Mohammed Siad Barre, was toppled.
</P>
<P>
Some 460 Somali representatives kicked off in May the country's
national reconciliation conference in Djibouti based on a
Djiboutian proposal. The conference established a 245-member
transition parliament on August 13, which elected Abdiqasim Salad
Hassan the Somali president. Both the parliament and the president
are the first in Somalia in a decade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
