<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Calls for Unconditional Release of Abducted Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of the Economic Community
of West African States (ECOWAS) and Mali President Alpha Konare
has called for the "immediate and unconditional release" of the 12
soldiers abducted by a Sierra Leone rebel group.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released by the secretariat of the 16-member
organization in the Nigerian capital Abuja, Konare condemned
vigorously the abduction of the soldiers, who wee serving under
the British training team in the war-torn west African country.
</P>
<P>
The statement came after reports that the Sierra Leonean
government and the United Nations were still in the process of
negotiating with the captors, who earlier set a number of
conditions for the release of the soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Konare appealed to all the parties concerned in Sierra Leone to
respect the framework of the Lome Peace Accord, signed by the
government and the rebels last July to end the country's eight-
year-old civil war.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers, 11 Britons and one Sierra Leonean, were captured
by the rebel group, known as the West Side Boys, last Friday when
they were patrolling along the Freetown-Masiaka highway. 
</P>
</TEXT>
