<DOCNO> XIE20000828.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 13 Parties Sign Burundi Peace Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ARUSHA, Tanzania, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Thirteen of the 19
Burundi warring parties Monday night signed a historic peace
agreement aimed at ending the seven-year-old civil war in Burundi
in the northern Tanzanian town of Arusha.
</P>
<P>
Among the signatories are the Burundi government, the Burundi
National Assembly, seven Hutu parties and four major Tutsi parties.
However, there are still six Tutsi parties which refuse to sign
the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Burundi President Pierre Buyoya signed the 175-page Peace and
Reconciliation Agreement on behalf of his government.
</P>
<P>
The agreement contains five protocols on the nature of the
conflicts, democracy and good governance, peace and security,
reconstruction and development, and guarantees on agreement
implementation.
</P>
<P>
The signing ceremony at the Arusha International Conference
Center was witnessed by dozens of heads of state and government
including U.S. President Bill Clinton and representatives from the
United Nations, the Organization of African Unity and the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
According to Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni, who chairs the
signing ceremony, the signing of the agreement is open and any
party which has not signed yet is welcome to sign it.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremony, facilitator of the Burundi peace
talks and former South African president Nelson Mandela, Tanzania
President Benjamin Mkapa and Clinton all commended the concerned
parties over their achievement.
</P>
<P>
They called on the various parties to show far-sightedness and
courage and make choice in the interests of the majority of the
people. The international community will firmly support those who
seek peace in Burundi, they said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Mandela strongly criticized some pro-Tutsi parties for
refusing to sign the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in the northern Tanzanian town of Arusha, Mandela said
some pro-Tutsi parties are only concerned with their own interests,
regardless of those of the people and the nation.
</P>
<P>
The Burundi peace talks was initiated by former Tanzanian
president Julius Nyerere in June 1998 and have been beefed up by
Mandela since he succeeded Nyerere as the facilitator in December
1999 following the latter's death of leukemia.
</P>
<P>
More than 200,000 people, mostly civilians, have been killed in
Burundi since civil war erupted in October 1993 when the country's
first democratically elected president Melchior Ndadaye, a Hutu,
was assassinated by pro-Tutsi soldiers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
