<HEADLINE> U.S. President Pays Maiden Visit to Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 28 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton arrived in Tanzania on Monday afternoon for a brief yet
historic visit to the eastern African country, during which he met
President Benjamin Mkapa and witnessed the negotiations for a
peace agreement by various Burundian parties in the northern
Tanzanian town of Arusha.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, the first U.S. incumbent president to visit Tanzania,
held brief discussions with his Tanzanian counterpart on issues of
mutual interest and cooperation between the two countries at the
VIP lounge of the Kilimanjaro International Airport shortly after
the touchdown of his plane.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who just finished a visit during the weekend to
Nigeria, praised Tanzania for its efforts in carrying out economic
reforms at home and bring peace to neighboring Burundi.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government will encourage more foreign investment in
Tanzania, Clinton said, adding that it will also support Tanzania
in its efforts to deal with the current drought and refugee
problems.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Mkapa briefed his U.S. counterpart on the
tremendous social, political and economic progress that Tanzania
has so far achieved.
</P>
<P>
These include the fiscal, financial and prudent budgetary
measures that Tanzania has continued to maintain as well as issues
related to austere steps to instill the rule of law and good
governance, especially the serious efforts taken to stamp out
corruption in the entire Tanzanian social fabric.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents also witnessed the signing of an open skies
agreement between the two countries, under which each party should
grant planes of the other party the right to fly across its
territory without landing and the right to make stops for non-
traffic purposes.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania and the United States have enjoyed good relations for
many years. The American investment in Tanzania has reached 26
million U.S. dollars. Besides, the United States is rated as
Tanzania's leading single source market for tourism, with over 50,
000 American tourists coming to Tanzania in 1999, earning the
country over 55 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania is Clinton's second leg of his three-nation African
trip. He left Arusha on Monday night for Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
