<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Attaches Importance to Mideast Peace Talks: Ecevit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Turkey attaches "vital" importance
to the Middle East peace process and "is ready to do its best" to
contribute to it, Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit said here on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark at a joint news conference following his
talks with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, who arrived in the
Turkish capital Ankara Monday for a brief working visit.
</P>
<P>
Barak said that Israel "is grateful" for Turkey's efforts and
initiatives within the framework of Mideast peace process, and will
take steps to further improve bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
But the two premiers did not elaborate about their talks that
diplomatic sources said focused on defense cooperation, the
Manavgat water project, through which Turkey wants to sell water to
Israel, and the faltering Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Barak, who is also defense minister,was due specifically to
discuss four major Turkish defense contracts for which Israeli
firms are bidding, his security advisor Danny Yatom said earlier.
</P>
<P>
The four projects, for which several foreign big companies are
competing, include the supply of Turkey's first spy satellite and a
fleet of 145 attack helicopters, the modernization of 160 U.S.-
built tanks, and the sale to Turkey of Israeli's airborne radar
system.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and its Jewish ally have carried out cooperations in
military training and Israeli firms have upgraded Turkish fighter
jets.
</P>
<P>
This was Barak's third visit to Turkey since he took office in
July last year. Israeli acting Foreign Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat had visited Turkey earlier.
</P>
<P>
Israel and the Palestinians have exerted intensive diplomatic
efforts to to garner support in the wake of the collapse of the U.
S.-sponsored Camp David peace summit on July 25.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian summit failed to produce an agreement
maily because of the dispute over the fate of East Jerusalem,
claimed by both sides.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem visited Gaza last Wednesday
and met with Arafat. The meeting was characterized by Palestinians
as "a very positive and constructive one."
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side has always asked Turkey to play a more
active and assertive role as a country which is heir to the Ottoman
Turks, who ruled the Middle East for almost four centuries.
</P>
<P>
Arab diplomatic sources said that Arafat had reminded Turkish
officials that the Ottoman Army's withdrawal from Jerusalem was
very recent, namely 83 years ago, in a bid to stress that Turkey
was by nature and definition an indispensable and more active
player in the region.
</P>
<P>
Echoing Arafat's remarks, Cem has indicated several times that
the status of Jerusalem "is an issue for the whole Muslims,"
certainly "a very important issue" for Muslim Turkey as well.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Barak wanted to be informed about the
Palestinian reaction to Turkey's proposals on the two thorniest
issues, including the status of Jerusalem and its holy sites, which
Cem had explained during his meeting with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
The Israelis declared that the United States is the sole
mediator on the issue of Jerusalem, obviously fearing that Turkey
will add its weight on the side of its Palestinian brotherhood.
</P>
<P>
Ankara maintains close relations with both Israel and Palestine.
Despite its diplomatic ties with the Palestinians, Turkey has also
built a strong alliance with the Jewish state since 1996 when they
signed a military cooperation deal.
</P>
<P>
The deal, causing unease among Muslim countries in the Mideast,
was viewed as part of attempts by the two countries to contain
their common rivals Syria and Iran in the region.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that Ankara is trying to pursue a balanced
position between its Muslim brotherhood Palestine and its Mideast
ally Israel.
</P>
<P>
During Arafat's visit to Ankara early this month, Turkish
leaders did not clearly express their supports for Arafat's would-
be unilateral declaration of Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
But they stressed Ankara's sensitivity over Jerusalem, urging
the Israeli government to review its policies over the holy places
in the city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000828.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Opposition Set to Win in First Stage of Parliamentary Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The opposition camp, led by former
Prime Minister Rafik Hariri, is set to pick up more than half of
the 63 parliamentary seats in northern and central Lebanon
provinces, local media said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Druze overlord Walid Jumblat has grabbed all eight seats
allotted to the Chouf region and most of the nine seats of the
Aley-Baabda constituency, Oriental radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The pro-government newspaper Nida Alwatan conceded defeat by
screaming "political, financial feudalism advance in first election
round," a reference to Jumblat and billionaire Hariri, pillars of a
opposition alliance swearing to oust Prime Minister Salim Hoss'
government.
</P>
<P>
The anti-government alliance, formed by Agriculture Minister
Suleiman Franjieh and Public Works Minister Najib Mikati, was
certain to win at least 13 of the 17 seats allotted to the Tripoli-
Zgorta constituency in northern Lebanon, An Nahar newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Some 600,000 voters turned out at the polls to elect a total of
63 deputies for northern Lebanon, the Christian heartland and the
Druze hinterland northeast and southeast of Beirut on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
No major security breaches were reported in most constituencies
during Sunday's 10-hour polling.
</P>
<P>
Some 10,000 army troops and 12,000 policemen were reported to
have guarded the polls in northern and central Lebanon as an
estimated average of 51 percent of the eligible voters cast their
ballots, undeterred by right-wing Christian calls for a nationwide
boycott to protest Syria's domination of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Michel Murr said the turnout average was 46
percent in northern Lebanon and 57 percent in the Mount Lebanon
province.
</P>
<P>
In North province, 28 deputies will be picked up from 145
candidates while in Mount province 35 deputies from 141 candidates.
</P>
<P>
The rest of 65 parliament members will be chosen from the areas
of Beirut, the Bekaa Valley and the South on Sunday. The liberated
area in south Lebanon will see the fist election after a 22-year
Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
Official results of Sunday's parliamentary polls -- the first of
a two-stage election to fill the legislature's 128 seats -- were
expected to be announced later Monday.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon is one of the few countries in the world whose elections
are run on sectarian lines, with the 128 parliamentary seats
divided equally among Muslims and Christians. The shares are also
sub-divided between each of the 18 recognized religious sects.
</P>
<P>
According to Lebanese law, the current government will resign
after the formation of the new parliament. The president will
nominate a premier who has to be approved by the parliament. Then
the premier will form a new government in a month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
