<HEADLINE> Iraq Hit by Worst Drought in a Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Some Iraqi National Assembly
(parliament) members have proposed ways to ease the severe water
shortage caused by drought, a report reaching here said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Tariq Abed Lafta, head of the People's Affairs Committee in the
National Assembly, said that the legislators have suggested to cut
the water supply to garages and ice-making factories to save water.
</P>
<P>
Acute lack of water equipment has worsened the water shortage
problem, Lafta said, adding that Iraq is in urgent need of a large
number of generators to produce enough electricity to pump water to
areas lack of water.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has signed contracts with foreign countries to import water
pumps, pipes and other equipment to improve the situation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the United Nations oil-for-food program, Iraq is allowed
to export oil to import food, medicine and other humanitarian
supplies to help offset the crippling impacts of the U.N.
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has complained that many contracts it signed with foreign
companies on purchase of equipment, materials and spare parts to
cope with drought have been put on hold by the U.N. Sanctions
Committee.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has suffered from drought for two successive years, but it
is widely believed that the drought this year is much worse than
that of the last year.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the drought this year is the most severe one
ever recorded in the past 100 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
