<HEADLINE> GCC FMs to Review Recent Gulf Situation: Kuwaiti FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) states will review the latest situation
in the Gulf region at their 76th meeting due in Saudi Arabia next
Friday, Kuwaiti foreign minister said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah said the meeting "will be topped
with position toward Iraq and the situation in the Gulf, the
Iranian occupation of UAE's three islands and the recent
development in the Middle East peace process."
</P>
<P>
And the ministers will review Iraq's implementation of United
Nations resolutions related to its invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the GCC countries -- Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman,
Qatar, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates (UAE) -- are
unified in calling on Baghdad to implement all the U.N. resolutions
to pave the way for the lifting of the 10-year international
embargo on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti official also said the GCC position is united in
underlining the importance of Iraq's showing good intentions
towards its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
"The meeting comes in a delicate period... we hope to reach
adequate recommendations to go hand-in-hand with this period,"
Sheikh Sabah said without elaborating.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the dispute over three Gulf islands between the UAE
and Iran, Sheikh Sabah said that the GCC foreign ministers will
review the latest developments in this issue, in light of the
efforts of a tripartite GCC committee instructed to work out a
mechanism for direct UAE-Iranian talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
