<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> URGENT: Pro-Tutsi Parties Refuse to Sign Burundi Peace Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ARUSHA, Tanzania, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Facilitator of the
Burundi peace talks and former South African president Nelson
Mandela Monday night accused pro-Tutsi parties of being reluctant
to sign a historic peace agreement aimed at ending the seven-year-
old civil war in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in the northern Tanzanian town of Arusha, Mandela said
the pro-Tutsi parties are only concerned with their own interests,
regardless of those of the people and the nation.
</P>
<P>
The Burundi peace talks was initiated by former Tanzanian
president Julius Nyerere in June 1998 and have been beefed up by
former South African president Nelson Mandela since he succeeded
Nyerere as the facilitator in December 1999 following the latter's
death of leukemia.
</P>
<P>
More than 200,000 people, mostly civilians, have been killed in
Burundi since civil war erupted in October 1993 when the country's
first democratically elected president Melchior Ndadaye, a Hutu,
was assassinated by pro-Tutsi soldiers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000828.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA Member States Urged to Attract Direct Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Commerce, Trade and
Industry Minister William Harrington Monday urged the Common
Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) member states to
tackle the issues of low levels of direct investment and the
unequal distribution of inflows as a matter of priority.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a three-day COMESA workshop on the establishment of
a regional investment facility here in Lusaka, Harrington said
investment inflow in Africa has been the lowest on a global scale
among the developing countries.
</P>
<P>
It declined from 9.4 billion U.S. dollars in 1997 to 8.3
billion dollars in 1998, he said.
</P>
<P>
He challenged the COMESA member states to strengthen political
and macro-economic stability in the region so that foreign direct
investment can be increased.
</P>
<P>
The continent remains a highly profitable investment
destination as companies receive rates of return on their
investments, he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking earlier, COMESA Secretary-General Erastus Mwencha
commended the Foreign Investment Advisory Service, a joint
facility of the International Finance Corporation and the World
Bank, for organizing the workshop that aims at attracting
investment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
This would also help in the joint tackling of poverty and
unemployment in the region as a whole, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
