<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Journalists to Help Correct Zimbabwe's Image </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 28 (Xinhua) -- A group of European journalists,
having seen for themselves what Zimbabwe has to offer as a tourist
destination, have taken the initiative to correct the country's
battered image and market it abroad.
</P>
<P>
The 10 nationals working for daily newspapers and tourist
publications from Austria, Switzerland and Germany have been in
the country for the past nine days, during which they visited
several tourist resorts including the Victoria Falls in
northwestern Zimbabwe, which is one of the seven wonders of the
world.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the eve of their departure, they held a meeting with
Zimbabwe's Environment and Tourism Minister Francis Nhema for one-
and-half hours, after which they pledged to repair the negative
perception with which Zimbabwe is being viewed abroad, the
Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"We want to tell Europe that Zimbabwe is not as bad as is being
portrayed. Because of the bad publicity, Europeans now think that
white farmers in Zimbabwe are not only being killed, but being
thrown out of the country as well," said Franz Josef Jedek, leader
of the group.
</P>
<P>
At least five white farmers were killed in violence leading to
the June 24-25 parliamentary election, but Jedek said the picture
created in Europe was much worse than what was on the ground.
</P>
<P>
Under normal circumstances, Zimbabwe's tourism sector generates
about 200 million U.S. dollars annually, but tourism officials
Monday said between 55 and 60 percent of the normal tourism
arrivals came into the country between January and August this
year.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Nhema noted that due to the bad publicity,
the perception overseas was that Zimbabwe was "burning".
</P>
<P>
"Many of these small incidents are over-dramatized," the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
"We have had incidents of violence over land re-distribution,
but violence is not a policy of the government," he said, noting
that "it is difficult to share land, where for instance the land
has been unfairly distributed over the past 100 years."
</P>
<P>
Whites, who constitute 1 percent of the total population,
currently own 70 percent of Zimbabwe's best land. 
</P>
</TEXT>
