<HEADLINE> S. African Defense Minister Slams Attack on Officers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Attacks on two senior South
African National Defense Force officers was a sign of a sick
society, said Defense Minister Mosiuoa Lekota in a statement on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Expressing shock and disgust at the attacks, Lekota said he had
instructed SANDF chief General Siphiwe Nyanda to urgently
institute an inquiry into the two incidents taking place on August
18 and Last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Sergeant-Major Moses Mangalo, who was
investigating the disappearance of 2000 AK47 rifles from the army,
was attacked under mysterious circumstances on August 18 and
admitted to a Military Hospital with a cracked skull.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, defense intelligence Brigadier Amos Lingisi, who
reportedly had information about those responsible for the theft
of the rifles, was also attacked in Durban and is still in a coma
at an unnamed hospital.
</P>
<P>
The Star newspaper reported on Monday that senior defense
officials believed the attacks on the two men were linked.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, colleagues, friends and family of Mangalo who
regained consciousness on Monday, expressed fear that he might be
poisoned in hospital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
