<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moscow Fire Service Confirms TV Tower Fire Put Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The fire raging in Moscow's
Ostankino television tower for over 24 hours has been extinguished
by 5:40 p.m. Moscow time (1340 GMT) Monday, the city fire service
announced Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
Fire fighters examined the TV tower all the way from the 63-
meter mark up to the 357-meter peak and found no sources of
ignition, the Interfax news agency cited Leonid Korotchik, chief
of the state fire-fighting service, as saying.
</P>
<P>
A short circuit is most likely the reason for the TV tower fire,
according to a preliminary investigation by law enforcement
officers at the scene.
</P>
<P>
The short circuit could have been caused by overloaded, worn-
out equipment or neglect for operational procedures.
</P>
<P>
The final answer to what led to the fire will be given by a
special commission on the elimination of the after-effects of the
blaze and by the operative group investigating the Ostankino
disaster, said Korotchik.
</P>
<P>
According to latest reports, two people killed by an elevator
drop in the fire have been identified as Col. Vladimir Arsyukov,
deputy chief of the fire service of the city's Northwestern
District, and elevator operator Svetlana Loseva, said the press
service of the Russian Emergency Situations Ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
