<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Hopes Hostages In Sierra Leone Be Released Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Speaking to the press, Annan said "they (officials) are talking
to the rebels who have taken these soldiers. And there are
expectations that they will be released and progress will be made,
and I hope that will be the case."
</P>
<P>
"I think we cannot ignore or condone this tendency in Sierra
Leone for rebels to take peacekeepers hostage. And as you know, we
are taking steps to strengthen the peacekeepers, to give them the
tools that they need to be able to defend themselves and their
mandate," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"And I think the rebels have to be careful not to go around
believing that it is easy to take peacekeepers as hostage, because
they do have robust rules of engagement and they are going to be
defending themselves. And I hope they (rebels) will be dissuaded
from pursuing this tack," he added.
</P>
<P>
The British soldiers, part of a contingent of about 400 who are
training a new Sierra Leone army, went missing on Friday in the
Masiaka-Forodugu area some 100 kilometers east of Freetown, the
capital of the country.
</P>
<P>
About 500 U.N. peacekeepers were held hostage for several weeks
by rebels of the Revolutionary United Front in May.  
</P>
</TEXT>
