<DOCNO> XIE20000828.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lockerbie Trial Adjourned Over Sensitive Information </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAMP ZEIST, Netherlands, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The Lockerbie
trial was adjourned on Monday after the defense team asked for
more time to study the sensitive documents released by the CIA of
the United States.
</P>
<P>
Defense lawyers asked for more time to scrutinize the new
information released by the American secret service to prepare
their cross-examination.
</P>
<P>
The defense had until now only seen edited copies of some CIA
cable communications from CIA agents in Malta, where they
interviewed Abdul Majid Giaka, a Libyan secret service agent who
later became U.S. double agent.
</P>
<P>
Defense lawyer Richard Keen said some issues would have to be
settled before CIA documents could be used as court evidence while
another defense lawyer William Taylor pointed out those which did
not tally with previous information.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution formerly gave the court as evidence the edited
copies of the cable communications, saying that the blanked-out
sections and words contain either sensitive or irrelevant
information.
</P>
<P>
Presiding judge Lord Sutherland adjourned the trial until
Tuesday saying that it was a regrettable situation but the three
judges of the trial had little choice.
</P>
<P>
Abdel Basset al-Megrahi and Al-Amin Khalifa Fahima are accused
of posing as Libyan Arab Airlines employees in Malta where they
loaded a suitcase bomb onto a Frankfurt-bound plane.
</P>
<P>
The suitcase bomb was later transferred onto Pan Am Flight 103.
The mid-air explosion over Lockerbie on December 21, 1988, killed
259 people on board the Boeing jumbo and 11 others on the ground.
</P>
<P>
The cable communications and the testimony scheduled to be
given by Giaka himself are expected to serve as the telling
evidence against the two accused. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
