<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Minister to Be in Tripoli to Receive Released Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 28 (Xinhua) -- French Minister-Delegate Charles
Josselin will fly to Tripoli, Libya, on Tuesday to receive the
three French women who were released on Sunday by their kidnappers
in southern Philippines, Agence France-Presse reported.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Muslim rebels released six foreign hostages on
Sunday after Libya mediated for their release for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
Five of the hostages released -- French nationals Sonia
Wendling and Maryse Burgot, Marie Moarbes of French-Lebanese
double nationality, South African national Monique Strydom and
German national Werner Wallert, were kidnapped on April 23 by the
rebels of the group Abu Sayyaf on the Malaysian island of Sipadan
and had been kept under captivity in the island of Jolo in the
southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Maryse Burgot is a French television journalist, kidnapped on
July 9 when she was reporting the situation of the hostages.
</P>
<P>
One German boy and three French nationals are still held by the
rebels in Jolo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
