<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Earns Another 479 Million U.S. Dollars in U.N. Oil-for-Food Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Iraq earned some 479
million U.S. dollars last week from exporting more than 17.2
million barrels of oil, the U.N. reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Office of the Iraq Program, which
administers the U.N. humanitarian oil-for-food program, said since
the program's current six-month period, known as "phase VIII",
began on June 9, Iraq has exported 155.7 million barrels of oil
worth more than 3.8 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the United Nations Security Council's sanctions
monitoring panel approved one contract for the sale of Iraqi oil
under phase VIII, bringing the total of approved contracts within
the phase to 98 with a total volume of nearly 384 million barrels,
the Office said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, humanitarian supplies and equipment for the oil
industry continued to arrive normally last week, it added.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under U.N. sanctions since its invasion of Kuwait
in 1990. The oil-for-food program began to implement in late 1996
which was aimed to ease the deteriorating humanitarian situation
in the country caused by the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions cannon be lifted until Iraq has destroyed all its
weapons of mass destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
