<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People Have Final Say in Iran's Presidential Election: Reformer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian people will have the
final say in the next presidential election to be held in 2001,
said a prominent leader of Iran's reformist movement on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The people will have the last say and there will be no need
for "disturbances and ballyhoo," said Mohammad Reza Khatami, the
younger brother of President Mohammad Khatami, the Islamic Republic
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Reza Khatami heads the Islamic Iran Participation Front, the
most influential reformist party in the country. He is also vice
speaker of the reformist-controlled Majlis (parliament).
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the people will vote for President Khatami's
reform programs in the next presidential election, possibly to be
held in May.
</P>
<P>
The presidential election in 1997 and the Majlis election last
February all showed that the people have clear support for reforms,
and the people will express their wishes in the voting next year,
Khatami said.
</P>
<P>
He also warned conservatives in the country not to act against
the people's wishes. "With a clear mandate for the reform programs
in last presidential and parliamentary elections, some individuals
should not oppose the people's wishes," he said.
</P>
<P>
President Khatami, who won an overwhelming victory in the 1997
presidential election, has announced that he will seek a second
term next year. He has also vowed to continue his political and
social reform programs.
</P>
<P>
The announcement made the conservatives nervous, as they had
just suffered another humiliating defeat in February's Majlis
election.
</P>
<P>
But with their control over such powerful organs as the
judiciary and other privileges inherited from the 1979 Islamic
revolution, the conservatives will surely exert severe pressures on
the reformers and try to stage a comeback in the 2001 election.
</P>
<P>
Reza Khatami on Monday also defended the performances of his
brother's government in the past three years, especially in the
economic area, which is often criticized by the conservatives.
</P>
<P>
Some people accuse the government of not doing enough on
economic issues, but the government has actually taken extensive
measures to solve economic problems over the past three years, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He cited the third five-year development plan (March 2000-March
2005) as a major achievement of the government in the economic
field.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the government is not solely responsible for
the country's economic development. In an open environment, and
with cooperation between the executive and legislative branches,
problems will be resolved, he said.
</P>
<P>
Currently, people support the government, despite its less than
complete success in some of the programs, he pointed out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
