<HEADLINE> Bodies Found in Crashed Lift in Russian TV Tower Basement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The bodies of those who went
missing in Moscow's Ostankino TV tower fire on Sunday were found
in a crashed elevator on Monday evening, reported the Itar-Tass
news agency.
</P>
<P>
The elevator was found on the Seventh underground floor of the
tower. It lay in water, firefighters said.
</P>
<P>
Investigators have already called in relatives to identify the
bodies. They did not say how many corpses were found in the
elevator.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the city's fire service said an elevator believed to
have carried three people fell down to the earth during the fire
that had been raging inside the tower for more than 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
The elevator is lying in the basement seven meters below ground,
and a counterpoise lying on the top of the elevator impeded rescue
operations, said the fire service.
</P>
<P>
The elevator is heavily compacted. Firefighters have pumped out
water that had accumulated inside the basement as the fire was
being extinguished.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Rescuers and firefighters have completed the
inspection of two elevator shafts 348 and 370 metres above the
ground in the tower crippled by fire.
</P>
<P>
They have also checked the machine room and the technical floor.
No lifts or people were found there.
</P>
<P>
Elevators did not run higher than 370 metres in the 540-meter-
high tower. 
</P>
</TEXT>
