<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Architect Warns Against TV Tower Disbalance  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 28 (Xinhua) -- An outstanding Russian TV tower
designer warned late Monday that the upper part of the tower
Ostankino in Moscow may lose its balance after suffering a night-
and-day heavy fire and fall down to the earth.
</P>
<P>
"I have no doubts about the current stability of the tower
itself, but I fear that its upper part -- the metal spire above
the 385 meter mark may lose its balance and drop to the ground,"
the Interfax news agency quoted Vladimir Milashevsk, chief
architect of the Moscow TV tower project, as saying.
</P>
<P>
The components of the tower were designed with a stability
ratio 2, which means that the carrying structures can stand loads
twice the weight of the tower itself, he said, supported by head
of the tower construction project, Vladimir Travush.
</P>
<P>
Milashevsky said that the tower had been designed with an eye
on possible damage to the steel cables keeping it intact from top
to bottom.
</P>
<P>
"It was designed so that even if all of the cables were cut off,
it would not mean that the building would collapse," he said.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, he expressed doubts that the stability of the
metal spire attached to the concrete part of the tower at the 385-
meter level may be broken by the fire.
</P>
<P>
"The high temperatures brought about by cables burning could
have a very bad effect on the condition of the metal spire," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Interfax also cited a Russian Emergencies Ministry
official taking part in extinguishing the fire as saying that the
tower will not collapse because the central steel ropes inside it
remain intact.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Ekho Moskvy (Echo of Moscow) radio said that half
of the steel ropes supporting the TV tower have been burnt broken,
which would have destroyed the balance state of the tower as a
whole despite the fact that no dangerous deformation is visible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
