<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Policeman Killed in Unrest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 28 (Xinhua) -- A policeman was killed Sunday
night in violent clashes in Iran's western city of Khoramabad, the
capital of Lorestan province, the Islamic Republic News Agency
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The city has been the scene of a political violence over the
past few days between supporters and opponents of the country's
most influential pro-reform student group -- the Office to Foster
Unity (OFU), which is currently holding its seventh annual
conference.
</P>
<P>
Some people rallied in support of the conference, but opponents
to the country's reformist movement tried to disturb the rallies
and the conference itself, which led to violent clashes.
</P>
<P>
The rioters killed a policeman and wounded some others and
inflicted damages to some banks and shops, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Reza Abdollahi, a security official in the province, blamed "
opportunists" for the unrest and stressed that no political group
was involved. He said some of the rioters have been arrested.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ali Tajernia, a member of the National Security and
Foreign Policy Commission in the Majlis (parliament), said Monday
that he will ask the Majlis to launch an investigation into the
incident.
</P>
<P>
The situation went worse due to some interventions and
mishandling of the issue, the lawmaker said, adding that the Majlis
should probe into its root cause.
</P>
<P>
Political rifts between Iran's two major political camps, namely
the conservative establishment and the nascent reformers, have
escalated since the latter won an overwhelming victory in
February's parliamentary election.
</P>
<P>
The conservatives, who are still in control of most of the
country's state organs, have stepped up their efforts to undermine
the reformist campaign initiated by President Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
So far more than 20 pro-reform papers and journals have been
banned from publishing and a number of reformist figures have been
imprisoned on charges of violating Islamic principles and
advocating American-style reforms.
</P>
<P>
Rallies and demonstrations are also frequent in Iran, as
different political groups try to mobilize support from the people,
especially young students. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000828.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Unveils E-Commerce Venture Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government Monday
said that companies setting up e-commerce ventures listed abroad
should bring down foreign stake to 74 percent in India within five
years of business.
</P>
<P>
An official release said here that the divestment should be
made in favor of Indian public within five years.
</P>
<P>
"It is clarified that disinvestment of 26 percent of equity in
favor of the Indian public in five years would be applicable in
cases where the foreign equity contribution is more than 74
percent and up to 100 percent," it said.
</P>
<P>
It said that these companies would engage only in business to
business (B2B) e-commerce and not in retail trading.
</P>
<P>
The government said that the foreign investors would be
required to divest their equity only to the extent it exceeds 74
percent to the Indian public.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Direct Investment up to 100 percent in e-commerce
activities shall remain under the automatic route and prior
approval of the Foreign Investment Promotion Board, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
