<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Largest Banking Group's Profit Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's largest banking
group, Malayan Banking Bhd (Maybank), recorded an unaudited group
pre-tax profit of 2.137 billion ringgit (0.56 billion U.S. dollars)
for the financial year which ended June 30, 2000, up 111 percent
from that in the corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
Its operating profit was up 11.4 percent to 3.655 billion
ringgit(0.96 billion U.S. dollars) and net profit increased 40.3
percent to 1.36 billion ringgit (0.35 billion U.S. dollars)
respectively, Malayan Banking Managing Director A. Amirsham Abdul
Aziz announced here Monday.
</P>
<P>
All major subsidiaries recorded improved performance except for
Maybank Assurance Bhd which recorded a lower profit due to higher
claims and a decline in investment income, he said at a press
conference to announce the group's results.
</P>
<P>
The overseas operations of the Maybank group showed an overall
improvement in pre-tax profit to 200.3 million ringgit (52.71
million U.S. dollars) from 14.14 million ringgit (3.72 million U.S.
dollars) previously
</P>
<P>
The group's net non-performing loan (NPL) ratio as in June 2000
was 5.6 percent against 5.3 percent in June 1999 and the risk-
weighted capital ratio of the group as by June 30, 2000 was 15.2
percent, well above the international minimum standard of eight
percent.
</P>
<P>
Amirsham said Maybank is looking forward to be the dominant
financial and insurance services group after its proposed merger
program is completed.
</P>
<P>
The group expects its market share in commercial banking
operation to expand to 23 percent after the merger exercise from
18 percent currently, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
