<DOCNO> XIE20000828.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Economy Grows by 6.4 Percent in 1999-2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The Indian economy posted a
reasonably high rate of growth of 6.4 percent during 1999-2000
fiscal year despite a number of difficult domestic and
international developments such as Kargil war and sharp rise in
oil prices.
</P>
<P>
According to the annual report of the Reserve Bank of India
released Monday, the annual rate of inflation, on a point-to-point
basis, was 6.5 percent (or 3.8 percent excluding the impact of
rise in administered oil prices) during the fiscal year (April 1,
1999 - March 31, 2000).
</P>
<P>
The accretion to the foreign exchange reserves was about 5.564
billion U.S. dollars and the external current account deficit was
below one percent of the Gross Domestic Product, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the new impulses of the growth have
emerged from the private sector with private capital formation
moving up, financed primarily by private savings.
</P>
<P>
However, the report said that there were many concerns over the
country's economy. The fiscal position has not been strong enough
to share the burden of macro-economic adjustment. The variability
in both output growth and the inflation rate continued to exist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000828.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Begins Accepting Nominations for General Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Nominations for Sri Lanka's
October 10 general elections began on Monday with 21 political
parties and independent groups nominating their candidates.
</P>
<P>
An independent group from the central Nuwara Eliya district was
the first to hand in its nomination, said an official in the
Elections Department.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some political parties are racing to cobble together
alliances before the deadline for nominations expires next Monday.
</P>
<P>
The ruling People's Alliance has formed an alliance with an
ultra nationalist party MEP, or the People's United Front, while
opposition parties are also trying to cut deals and form alliances
with political counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's 45 recognized political parties and several
independent groups have indicated that they will contest in the
11th parliamentary general elections.
</P>
<P>
Some 12 million voters are to cast votes at more than 10,000
polling booths to elect 225 representatives to the next parliament.
</P>
</TEXT>
