<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore, Germany to Help Small, Medium Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 28 (Xinhua) -- A memorandum of understanding
(MOU) for reciprocal assistance was signed here Monday between
Singapore's Productivity and Standards Board (PSB) and the Center
for Productivity and Technology of Saarland State (CPT) of Germany
to help their SME).
</P>
<P>
The signing of the MOU opened the two-day discussions on
business opportunities between representatives of 48 local SMEs
and 15 companies from the Saarland state.
</P>
<P>
The German delegation led by Hanspeter Georgi, Minister of
Economic Affairs of the Saarland state government, is in Singapore
on a business matching mission under the PSB's Business Connect
program to take part in the exhibition of Hospimedica Asia opening
here tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
With the MOU, both parties are committed to working together to
promote collaborations that will benefit their SMEs in the sectors
of automotive, machine tools, environment technology, medicine
technique and information technology.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Senior Parliamentary Secretary (Trade &AMP; Industry) Tan
Guan Seng said at the signing ceremony that Singapore's SMEs will
be able to tap new technologies and use Saarland as a gateway to
Germany while the Saarland companies can leverage on Singapore's
SMEs to get into Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
Georgi said that SMEs form the backbone of the economy both in
good and in bad times and business matching remains important in
the new economic environment.
</P>
<P>
Former German Chancellor Helmut Kohl and Singapore Prime
Minister Goh Chok Tong signed the Enhanced Partnership in 1998
with an aim to strengthen relations between their governments and
peoples for mutual benefits through various ways.
</P>
<P>
Singapore and Germany have since established close ties. More
than 600 German companies are in Singapore with cumulative
investments of 4.5 billion deutsche marks (about 2.1 billion U.S.
dollars). Singapore is Germany's largest trading partner in
Southeast Asia and Germany is one of Singapore's top ten trading
partners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
