<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Approves EPO Tests for Sydney Olympic Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAUSANNE, SWITZERLAND, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The executive
board of the Internatinal Olympic Committee (IOC) approved to
introduce tests for the banned performance-enhancing drug
erythropoietin, or EPO, at the upcoming Olympic Games in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made on recommendation from the IOC Juridical
Commission, according to the IOC press release. Thus, during the
Sydney games, test consists of two elements, analysis of blood and
urine samples.
</P>
<P>
When both such elements are positive, the IOC said, the test
shall constitute a positive case of doping. Only one blood sample
of about 10 mls shall be required for purposes of the test, not
the usual "A" and "B" samples as are used for urine samples.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
