<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian City Heads Discuss Network of Major Cities in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The heads of four Asian
capital cities met here Monday to discuss the formation of a
network of major cities of Asia, known as "Asian Network of Major
Cities 21" and signed a joint declaration on the matter.
</P>
<P>
The chief minister of the National Capital Territory of Delhi,
the governor of the Metropolis of Tokyo and the mayors of the
Seoul Metropolitan Government and the Kuala Lumpur City stated in
the declaration that the purpose of the formation of the network
is to promote the development and prosperity of Asia as a whole.
</P>
<P>
"To ensure Asia plays a more significant role in the
international community of the 21st century, it is essential that
major cities of Asia forge even closer relationship," they said.
</P>
<P>
They considered the major cities as both the heart and the
brain of Asia and said that by collectively taking initiative in
building this network and deepening the social and economic bond
and cooperation, they will make a significant contribution to the
peace and prosperity of Asia in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The heads of the cities present decided that members of this
network shall include capital cities and/or major cities of Asia.
</P>
<P>
The cities participating in this network will cooperate in a
number of fields such as environment, urban planning, promotion of
arts, culture and tourism, human resource development, education,
women development, health, disaster prevention management and aid,
and technological development including information technology.
</P>
<P>
As a follow-up, they decided to hold the first Asian Network of
Major Cities 21 meeting in Tokyo in 2001.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference after the signing of the
declaration,the heads of the four cities said they are in the
process of inviting capital cities and major cities of Asia to
participate in the network in order to build new socioeconomic
relations.
</P>
<P>
Seoul Governor Goh Kun proposed at the joint press conference
that Pyongyang be invited to join the network.
</P>
<P>
The network is expected to have a clearer picture at the first
Asian Network of Major Cities 21 meeting in Tokyo next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
