<HEADLINE> Riot Occurs in Australian Refugee Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- A serious riot broke out Monday
at a refugees detention center in Australia.
</P>
<P>
The troubled Woomera center, 470 kilometers northwest of
Adelaide, shelters 800 people and it last saw unrest in June when
a number of detainees fled out.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Associated Press (AAP) reported that the rioters
set fire to buildings and tried to tear holes in the fence around
the center.
</P>
<P>
AAP quoted a guard as saying the rioters wore towels around
their heads to protect their identity during the 12-hour riot.
</P>
<P>
About 100 people were involved in the violent action and many
of them were recently refused refugee status.
</P>
<P>
A total of 250 guards and 50 police men used mobile water
cannon and tear gas to repel the rioting refugees.
</P>
<P>
At least 13 guards were reportedly injured. Police said most of
the injured guards suffered cuts and bruises.
</P>
<P>
Six buildings including a school and recreation room were
gutted by fire.
</P>
<P>
Immigration Minister Philip Ruddock said most of the asylum-
seekers arrived as boat people and the rioters would probably be
charged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
