<HEADLINE> Philippines Sticks to "One China" Policy: Estrada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada said here Monday that the Philippine government will
continue to follow the "One China" Policy.
</P>
<P>
Estrada made the remark at the presidential palace Monday
afternoon when he received credentials from Wang Chunqui, newly-
appointed Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary of the
People's Republic of China to the Republic of the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
He said that since the establishment of diplomatic relations
between the two countries in June 1975, the two have steadily
grown closer to each other.
</P>
<P>
"This is manifested in the exchange of high level visits," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin and Premier Zhu Rongji visited
the Philippines in 1996 and 1999 respectively. Estrada and
Philippine Vice President Gloria Macapagal-Arroyo paid visits to
China earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Estrada spoke highly of a Joint Statement on the Framework of
Bilateral Cooperation in the 21st Century signed between the two
countries last May, calling it "a milestone in our relations'
history."
</P>
<P>
Acknowledging that the two sides may have had differences, he
said, "but we have always agreed that these differences are best
resolved through peaceful dialogue and consultations."
</P>
<P>
"We have also resolved that our differences should not hinder
the development of our relations," he added.
</P>
<P>
Wang, on his part, said that over the past 25 years, the Sino-
Philippine relations, based on the five principles of peaceful
coexistence, have witnessed steady development, which he said has
not only benefited the two peoples feasibly but also contributed
to the peace and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his belief that through joint efforts by the two
governments and peoples, the cooperative relations of good
neighborliness and mutual trust between the two countries will
enjoy a stride in the new century.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese ambassador arrived in Manila on August 10. 
</P>
</TEXT>
