<HEADLINE> EU to Check Uganda's Conditions for Fish Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan Ministry of
Fisheries confirmed that the European Union (EU) will send an
inspection mission from October 2 to 6 to Uganda to check
conditions for its fish export to EU countries.
</P>
<P>
The EU mission will assess how far Uganda has fulfilled the
conditions that were set when the ban for fish export was
provisionally lifted on August 4, according to a press release
from the ministry Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the requirement for the EU market has been met and the
EU inspection mission in October will find evidence on the ground,
" said the release.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Fisheries Resources has provided a list of
official landing sites that handle fish for export, said the
release.
</P>
<P>
It said that there is a program for improvement of the fish
landing sites in both short-term and long-term, adding that the
landing sites need a bit of improvement but are generally
compliant.
</P>
<P>
The fish ban was imposed on Uganda's exports March last year,
citing poor hygiene, sanitation and the presence of pesticides in
the fishing waters. The ban cost the country close to 100 million
U.S. dollars of direct exports, revenues to the government,
incomes to fishermen and other related activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
