<HEADLINE> IOC Meets to Accept Candidate Cities for 2008 Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAUSANNE, SWITZERLAND, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The executive
board of the International Olmypic Committee (IOC) began a two-day
meeting on Monday to decide on the candidate cities for the 29th
Olympic Games in 2008.
</P>
<P>
By June 20, 2000, ten applicant cities submitted their answers
to the IOC questions concerning their organizational capacity to
host the 2008 Olympic Games. The ten applicant cities are Bangkok
of Thailand, Beijing of China, Cairo of Egypt, Havana of Cuba,
Istanbul of Turkey, Kuala Lumpur of Malaysia, Osaka of Japan,
Paris of France, Seville of Spain, and Toronto of Canada.
</P>
<P>
From June 21 to August 27, the IOC experts examined the replies
of the ten applicant cities. On the basis of the examination
results, the IOC executive board will select a certain number of
cities, likely less than half of the ten, as candidates to run in
the final phase for the 2008 Olympics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
