<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC to Check Implementation of Law of Neighborhood Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress (NPC), China's top legislature, is
scheduled to dispatch four teams in early September to check the
implementation of the Organic Law of the Urban Neighborhood
Committee.
</P>
<P>
The two-week inspection will cover such cities as Harbin,
Shanghai, Lanzhou and Kunming.
</P>
<P>
China now has 115,000 urban neighborhood committees, with a
total staff of 502,000. These committees deal with some 400
million urban Chinese, as well as some 70 million of China's "
floating population," most of whom come to cities from rural areas
to make a fortune.
</P>
<P>
The inspection teams held a plenary session at the Great Hall
of the People this morning.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Chunyun, vice-chairman of the NPC Standing Committee,
made a speech at the meeting, saying that the inspection is aimed
at finding out how well the Law has been implemented and
summarizing successful experiences.
</P>
<P>
Jiang pointed out that the inspection, which complies with
China's basic strategy of "governing the country in accordance
with law," will serve to promote the building of socialist
legislation.
</P>
<P>
The NPC Standing Committee has decided to carry out inspections
on the implementation of laws on township enterprises, land
management, urban neighborhood committee, and criminal procedures
within this year. Inspection of the previous two laws has been
done. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000828.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daily Air Quality Report for 42 Chinese Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Three Chinese cities, namely
Changsha, Chongqing and Lanzhou reported slight air pollution
today, with the highest pollution reading at 131 in Lanzhou.
</P>
<P>
According to the daily air quality report issued by the China
Environmental Monitoring Center, level two, or fairly good air
quality, was recorded in 29 other cities.
</P>
<P>
These cities are Beijing, Tianjin, Shijiazhuang, Taiyuan,
Hohhot, Shenyang, Dalian, Changchun, Harbin, Shanghai, Nanjing,
Suzhou, Hangzhou, Wenzhou, Nanchang, Jinan, Qingdao, Yantai,
Zhengzhou, Wuhan, Shenzhen, Zhanjiang, Nanning, Chengdu, Guiyang,
Xi'an, Xinning, Yinchuan and Urumqi.
</P>
<P>
Particulates less than 10 microns in size were the major
pollutants in most of these cities, except Shijiazhuang, Chongqing
and Guiyang, where sulfur dioxide was the major air pollutant.
</P>
<P>
Ten cities -- Nantong, Hefei, Fuzhou, Xiamen, Guangzhou, Zhuhai,
Shantou, Haikou, Kunming and Lhasa -- reported excellent air.
</P>
<P>
The center classifies air quality in China's urban areas into
five levels: level one or excellent (pollution reading: not
exceeding 50), level two or fairly good (pollution reading: 51 to
100), level three or slightly polluted (pollution reading: 101 to
200), level four or poor (pollution reading: 201 to 300), and
level five or hazardous (pollution reading: over 301).
</P>
<P>
The 42 cities monitored by the center include the four
municipalities of Beijing, Tianjin, Shanghai and Chongqing,
provincial capitals and major cities in the economically developed
coastal areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000828.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 40 Pollutant Power Plants Exposed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Authorities have
made public a list of the 40 polluting coal-burning power plants
in efforts to press local industries to pay greater attention to
environmental issues, according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
The 40 coal-powered units exposed by the State Environmental
Protection Administration each discharges more than 5,000 tons of
dioxide annually.
</P>
<P>
Up to the end of this June, local environmental authorities
shut down a total of 4,732 high-sulfur coal mines, 778 small
cement and glass production lines, 404 small iron and steel mills,
and 1,422 big polluters in other industries.
</P>
<P>
This has helped reduce sulfur discharge by 600,000 tons in
areas where authorities have been working to curb acid rain and
sulfur dioxide.
</P>
<P>
However, the air pollution still remains a serious problem in
these areas where 23 cities report extra sulfur content in the
atmosphere, while 12 cities are suffering from severe acid rain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000828.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Factories in Three Gorges Urged to Curb Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The State Environmental
Protection Administration (SEPA) has urged factories in the Three
Gorges area to bring pollution under control as required.
</P>
<P>
So far, about half of the factories, either in operation or
under construction in this area, are not up to the state pollution
control standards, posing a threat to the quality of water in the
middle and upper reaches of the Yangtze River covered by the huge
reservoir at the Three Gorges, the SEPA said.
</P>
<P>
According to the SEPA, a project in the Three Gorges area must
curb pollution right from stage of designing, construction to
operation.
</P>
<P>
A SEPA official attributed the situation in the Three Gorges to
the failure of local authorities who have not paid enough
attention to environmental protection and the implementation of
the environmental protection law.
</P>
<P>
All these factories which have failed to reached pollution
control standards will be ordered to suspend operation until their
anti-pollution equipment passes examinations, the official
stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
