<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Defense Forces (IDF) officers believe the three
soldiers from the elite Duvdevan unit killed late Saturday night in
an attempt to capture a senior Hamas member Mahmoud Abu Hanoud were
most likely shot by other soldiers, in what Chief of Staff Shaul
Mofaz called a "serious operational mishap."
</P>
<P>
A fourth soldier was moderately wounded in the raid.
</P>
<P>
Wounded in the shoulder, Abu Hanoud managed to reach the nearby
West Bank City of Nablus, where he turned himself in to the
Palestinian National Authority and was hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak is considering whether to ask
for Abu Hanoud's extradition.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- The Israeli Foreign Ministry is predicting that Islamic
Summit's Jerusalem Committee, convening Monday in Morocco, will not
adopt resolutions that will make it difficult for Palestinian
National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat to be flexible in his
negotiations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry analysts believe that Arafat called for the
meeting in order to gain support for a more militant stand on
Jerusalem, but Israel and the U.S. have in the last few days been
using all diplomatic channels at their disposal to block any
radical decision by the committee.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- The Israeli new school year, set for Friday, could be delayed
by a teachers strike that maybe continues after separate talks
between Finance Minister Avraham Shochat and heads of the two
teachers unions on teachers' salary demands failed Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Ehud Barak, who also holds the education
portfolio, renewed his promise to make education, especially in the
peripheral areas, his top priority, but said it would have to wait
for another year, promising a hefty budget increase in 2001.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister Barak is paying a day-long visit to Ankara to
brief the Turkish leadership on the recent developments in the
peace process with the Palestinians and to further the strategic
and defense cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Barak's visit coincides with the failure of Israeli defense
industries to win two important arms deals with Turkey. Barak's
absence during a crucial phase of the bid, which occurred during
the July 11-25 Camp David summit, was criticized as having a
detrimental effect on the outcome of the bid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
