<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesians Urged to Stay Calm Ahead of Soeharto Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Newly-appointed Coordinating
Minister for Political, Social and Security Affairs Susilo Bambang
Yudhoyono asked here Monday all Indonesians to stay calm,
particularly ahead of former President Soeharto's trial.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the people to exercise restraint and "not to
provoke any activities which will likely trigger violent action."
</P>
<P>
"The process of law, please go ahead. But we don't expect any
negative excess," Yudhoyono said, adding that there are views both
for and against the process of the trial of Soeharto on charges of
corruption during his 32 years of rule.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Attorney General Marzuki Darusman has reconfirmed
that Soeharto will be tried on Thursday, August 31, adding that if
Soeharto was to be absent from the trial, that would be due to
medical reasons.
</P>
<P>
He said the trial has been arranged and agreed upon by the
Attorney General's Office, the accused himself and his legal
counsel and the medical team.
</P>
<P>
Darusman also said the medical team observing the health of the
79-year-old man will examine the former strong man to make sure
that he is okay to show up before the court.
</P>
<P>
"And then, the attorney general will submit the result of the
examination to the chief of South Jakarta District Court to decide
(whether or not Soeharto is medically fit for the trial)," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said a trial in absentia is not applicable to
Soeharto as this could only be arranged by a ruling from the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
Last week, one of Soeharto's lawyers, Mohammad Assegaf,
indicated that the former ruler would not attend the trial, asking
the people to accept the likelihood of Soeharto's absence for
health reasons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
