<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Freed Hostages Leave Philippines for Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- A plane carrying six Sulu
hostages took off at Cebu International Airport in the southern
Philippines at around 4:40 p.m. (0840 GMT) Monday after a South
African male hostage reunited with his wife at the airport, the
news channel of the TV network ABS-CBN reported.
</P>
<P>
The six, who were freed Sunday and earlier Monday, were seen
waving bouquets and smiling as they were boarding.
</P>
<P>
Newly-released South African hostage Carel Strydom was finally
reunited with his wife, Monique, and four other freed captives
before the Libyan jet took off.
</P>
<P>
The joyful Strydoms were hugging and kissing upon seeing each
other after Carel, accompanied by chief Philippine government
negotiator Robert Aventajado, arrived at the Cebu Airport at 2:47
p.m.Monday.
</P>
<P>
The couple, together with the other four hostages freed Sunday,
will be flown to the Libyan capital of Tripoli, where they are
said to be met by their relatives and government officials of
their native countries.
</P>
<P>
Carel's brother, Sam Strydom, was quoted by the ABS-CBN as
saying,when asked if Monique told him anything about their ordeal
in the hands of the Abu Sayyaf, that Monique "only talked about
the future, not the past."
</P>
<P>
With Strydom's release, only five more males from the original
group of 21 hostages taken by the Abu Sayyaf in Malaysia's diving
resort of Sipadan on April 23 remain in captivity. They include
two Finns, one French, one German and one Filipino.
</P>
<P>
Besides, two other French male journalists taken on July 9
while covering the hostage drama are also in the hands of the
group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
