<HEADLINE> Putin Orders to Secure Blazing TV Tower, Resume Broadcasts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Vladimir Putin
ordered his ministers Monday to do every effort to extinguish the
fire raging in the country's central TV tower Ostankino and
quickly restore TV broadcasts and communication services.
</P>
<P>
"The latest emergency, the fire in the Ostankino TV tower, has
revealed the dire situation in vital installations and in the
country as a whole," Putin said at a meeting with cabinet members
in the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
He discussed immediate steps to ensure security around the
Ostankino tower and resume TV broadcasts to Moscow and the Moscow
region, according to the Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
"We should not forget the large-scale problems or current
economic issues here. Tenacious work along every line in the
economy will make such emergencies impossible," Putin stressed.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that Ostankino fire shows Russia in general is in a
plight and believes the situation can be changed only through
economic development.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Russian Prime Minister Mikhail Kasyanov vowed
to intensify work and find a way to resume TV broadcasts to Moscow
and its region, which stopped because of the tower fire.
</P>
<P>
Technical directors of Russian TV companies gathered in the
Russian Press Ministry at 11:00 hours Moscow time (0700 GMT) to
find a way out of the TV blackout.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, experts said broadcasts to Moscow and the
region can be resumed via cable TV networks. TV signal should be
transmitted via satellite to the existing networks in the capital
and most suitable are the NTV Plus and Kosmos TV.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, firemen are planning to flood the feeder cables with
foam at the height of 50 meters.
</P>
<P>
A headquarters spokesman said feeders' coating went on fire at
the height of 400 meters at 15:08 hours Moscow time (1108 GMT) on
Sunday. There was no automatic fire extinguishing system in that
place and the blaze began to spread down along the feeders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
