<DOCNO> XIE20000828.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli PM Due in Turkey for One-Day Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
is scheduled to make a one-day official visit to Turkey on Monday
to seek support in the stalled Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Barak will be greeted by Turkish President Ahmet Necdet Sezer
and will hold talks with Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit. Barak, who
is also Israeli Defense Minister, is also scheduled to meet with
Turkish Defense Minister Sabahattin Cakmakoglu.
</P>
<P>
Barak is expected to brief his hosts on the latest developments
in the Middle East peacemaking after the failed Camp David summit
between him, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and U.S. President
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
To the disappointment of all parties concerned, the two sides
fell into a deadlock primarily over the status of Jerusalem during
the 15-day U.S.-brokered meeting.
</P>
<P>
Israel claims Jerusalem, housing holy sites to Jews, Muslims and
Christians, as its "undivided and eternal capital," while the
Palestinians want the Arab East Jerusalem seized by Israel in the
1967 Mideast war as the capital of their future state.
</P>
<P>
Barak's talks will also dwell on military cooperation with
Turkey and the Manavgat Water Project, through which Turkey wants
to sell water to Israel.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, a Middle East predominantly Muslim but secular country,
has served as a stage for intense diplomatic activities in the wake
of the Camp David summit.
</P>
<P>
Ankara received Arafat, Israeli acting Foreign Minister Sholomo
Ben-Ami and United States Assistant Secretary of State Edward
Walker earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
However, Ankara has repeatedly denied that it has been playing
the role as mediator, saying it has been acting as "facilitator."
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have all along asked Turkey to play a more
active and assertive role in the peace process, particularly on the
issue of Jerusalem. But the Israelis have declared that the United
States is the sole mediator on the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000828.0191 </DOCNO>
