<HEADLINE> Freed S. African Hostage Met by Philippine Govt Negotiator </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- South African Carel Strydom, who
was freed by the Abu Sayyaf in its Sulu jungle lair earlier Monday
afternoon, has arrived in the nearby city of Zamboanga, where he
was turned over to the Philippines' chief government negotiator
Robert Aventajado.
</P>
<P>
In an interview at an air base in Zamboanga which was televised
through the ABS-CBN TV network, Strydom said emotionally that
although he is freed, yet it is "unfair to see other guys left
behind (in Abu Sayyaf's jungle hideout in Sulu)."
</P>
<P>
Following a short turnover ceremony in Zamboanga, Strydom,
accompanied by Aventajado and other local Philippine officials,
boarded the plane waiting to take him to another southern
Philippine city of Cebu to reunite with his wife, Monique, and
four other foreign hostages freed on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A chartered Libyan plane is reportedly waiting to take Strydom
and the other released hostages to Tripoli, capital of Libya.
Strydom was supposed to be included in the first batch of hostages
released Sunday but his freedom was stalled for still unknown
reasons.
</P>
<P>
Strydom is in apparent good health, wearing a colored T-shirt
and blue shorts. He was received in Tagbak, Sulu, which is 150
kilometers away from Zamboanga city, by Retired Gen. Guillermo
Ruiz, a senior aide of Aventajado.
</P>
<P>
With his release, only five more males from the original group
of 21 hostages taken by the Abu Sayyaf in Malaysia's diving resort
of Sipadan on April 23 remain in captivity. They include two Finns,
one French, one German and one Filipino.
</P>
<P>
Besides, two other French male journalists taken on July 9
while covering the hostage drama are also in the hands of the Abu
Sayyaf. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
