<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkana Tribesmen Move to Uganda for Pasture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of heavily armed Kenya
's Turkana tribesmen have crossed the border and settled with
their cattle in Uganda in recent weeks, raising fears of violent
conflict in a region already devastated by drought.
</P>
<P>
The herdsmen have abandoned their arid grazing grounds to keep
their large herds alive while they wait for rain, the major
newspaper Daily Nation reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
"There are about 5,000 men, women and children," said Ocero
Ogola, an aid worker delivering emergency food to Ugandan Dodoth
and Ik tribes in the area.
</P>
<P>
The Turkana tribesmen made a steep, difficult climb from the
floor of the Great Rift Valley to Kamion, which overlooks shady
woodland and long grass on the Ugandan side of the border.
</P>
<P>
Kamion, inhabited mainly by the small Ik tribe, normally acts
as a buffer zone between the Turkana and Uganda Dodoth herders,
who frequently raid each other's livestock.
</P>
<P>
The Ik, Dodoth and Turkana are at peace at the moment. But in
the sparsely-populated corner of Uganda, 420 km northeast of
Kampala, cattle raiding is endemic and every herder carries a gun.
</P>
<P>
"For the time being, i don't think there is going to be trouble,
" an Ik leader said. "But if Turkana try to take cattle from the
Dodoth there will be trouble."
</P>
<P>
The failure of three consecutive rainy seasons have caused
severe drought in the Horn of Africa and east Africa. About 10
million people, including 3.3 million Kenyans are threatened with
famine while livestock are dying in large numbers due to lack of
pasture.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
