<DOCNO> XIE20000828.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan President to Open African Governance forum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni is scheduled to open a three-day Fourth Africa Governance
Forum in Uganda on Friday, which is sponsored by the United
Nations Development Program (UNDP).
</P>
<P>
According to a statement available Monday, the annual Forum
will be attended by 100 delegates from over 10 African countries,
representatives of donor countries, civil society and
international organizations.
</P>
<P>
"Governance is recognized as a bedrock of development," UNDP
Administrator Mark Malloch Brown said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
"Without transparent and accountable institutions, and the
capacity to develop policies and laws to enable a country to
manage its markets and its political life, development is not
sustainable," said Brown.
</P>
<P>
He said it was clear that success in development was closely
related to the quality of governance, adding that open democratic
institutions allow full participation in politics.
</P>
<P>
The third Forum was held last year in Mali and deliberated on
conflict management and governance. Ghana hosted the second on "
accountability and transparency in Africa" while the inaugural one
was held in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, dealing with issues of
leadership building, strengthening parliamentary, judicial and
administrative systems and peace and stability, as well as free
and responsible press. 
</P>
</TEXT>
