<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise in Tokyo, Nikkei Closes Above 17,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices rose in Tokyo Monday
on active buying by foreign investors, with the benchmark Nikkei
index closing above 17,000 for the first time in six weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange surged 269.79 points, or 1.60
percent from last Friday's close to end at 17,181.12.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, added 12.35 points or 0.81 percent to 1,543.
63.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section decreased to 555.70 million
shares from last Friday's 614.87 million.
</P>
<P>
Mitsubishi Electric was the day's volume leader,
</P>
<P>
High-priced information technology issues drew buying while
semiconductor makers were strong on expectations for growth in
their earnings for the first half of fiscal 2000, trader said.
</P>
<P>
Nonlife insurers also gained on expectations for further
corporate realignment in the sector, they said.
</P>
<P>
The rubber, nonferrous metal and brokerage sectors also marked
sharp gains, while the construction, oil and real estate sectors
faced selling.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers exceeded
gainers 814 to 438 despite the rises in the Nikkei and TOPIX, with
148 issues closing unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
