<DOCNO> XIE20000828.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC to Commercialize Stock Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Stock Exchanges in The Southern
African Development Community (SADC) will soon start operating as
business houses rather than current membership houses, Zambia
Daily Mail newspaper reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Briefing the press following a two day workshop of the region's
committee of stock exchanges held in Lusaka, chairman of the
committee Jeoff Mhlanga said that stock exchanges within the
region had previously been run like associations, and that when
commercialized, they would run like conventional business
companies in a transparent manner.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted the chairman as saying the move was aimed at
integrating the SADC capital market.
</P>
<P>
"We demand that there is transparency and accountability in the
operations of stock exchanges. We have resolved that each member
state consider opening up its exchange as a way forward in a way
that conforms to the rest of the world," Mhlanga said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Lusaka Stock Exchange General Manager Charles Mate
said as the region was integrating into a Free Trade Area there
was need for stock exchanges to operate as businesses than where
members decided everything.
</P>
<P>
He said unlike in the past where trading was done by members
only, time has come to open up the trading to the general public.
</P>
<P>
He said the committee wants to give investors to trade on any
stock exchange in the region.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the SADC Stock Exchanges have
harmonized their listing procedures and would like to improve in
the trading, clearing and settlement systems to allow free flow of
capital in the SADC region.
</P>
<P>
The workshop resolved to de-mutualize the operations of the
exchanges, adopt specific arrangements based on the Johannesburg,
South Africa, stock exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
