<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Send Observers to Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will send 10
military personnel to Ethiopia as observers of the peacekeeping
force there.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has been asked by the United Nations to help out in
the disaster-stricken country and it was decided that the 10
officers were enough for the mission, Defense Minister Najib Tun
Razak said Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said the 10 officers would serve in Ethiopia for one year
but their departure had not been fixed as the UN had yet to notify
the Malaysian authorities on the date they were scheduled to
depart.
</P>
<P>
However, the 10 officers are on standby now, he told reporters
after meeting visiting Pakistani Defense Secretary Lt. Gen. Nasim
Rana here.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia would not send a bigger group in the form of a
battalion.
</P>
<P>
On the meeting with Nasim, Najib said Malaysia and Pakistan
were in the midst of discussion on ways to enhance defense
cooperation especially in the area of submarine maintenance.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has the ability and technology in the area of
submarine maintenance and Malaysia wants to learn from them, Najib
said, adding Pakistan is currently constructing a submarine with
assistance from France.
</P>
<P>
Nasim arrived here Saturday for the Malaysia-Pakistan Defense
Cooperation Joint Commission meeting and is expected to leave
Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
