<DOCNO> XIE20000828.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prepaid Mobile Phone Service Popular in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Low-end mobile-phone services
with no monthly fees are gaining popularity in Thailand,
especially among young people, the Bangkok Post reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Advanced Info Service (AIS) and Total Access Communication (TAC)
, the two local market leaders, are contemplating how to attract
more customers to their prepaid services.
</P>
<P>
The two companies now claim 10% of the country's cellular phone
market of three million users. TAC claims 100,000 customers and
AIS 212,400 for the year-old services.
</P>
<P>
Prepaid cellular services in Malaysia, the Philippines and
Italy accounted for more than half of the total cellular market
share, AIS marketing director Thitipong Keawpaisarn was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Even though prepaid service in Thailand is in the early stages,
the sales volume has been more than for the GSM system during the
last few months, which makes the company optimistic about the
business, he said.
</P>
<P>
Prepaid services offered many advantages over conventional
cellular service, including affordable prices, two-way
communications, and controllable fees, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Many Thai parents now give their children prepaid services
instead of buying them a cellular handset with fixed monthly fees,
because prepaying helps control expenditures.
</P>
<P>
Although prepaid services do not have a 500-baht (12.5 U.S.
dollars) monthly fee as regular mobile phone service charges,
operators make up for the difference with higher calling charges
than for conventional cellular services.
</P>
<P>
Handset prices for users of prepaid services are also lower, as
low-volume callers do not need a top quality model. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000828.0217 </DOCNO>
