<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Pledges to Shift to Knowledge-based Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi Monday stressed the importance of a
strategic shift towards a knowledge-based economy in order for
Malaysia to achieve its economic objectives of becoming a
developed country by the year 2020.
</P>
<P>
"The critical success factor in becoming competitive in the new
global economy rests with our ability to harness knowledge into
all areas of economic activities," he said at the opening of the
two-day Malaysian Business and Economic Summit here.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's push towards this endeavor is an undertaking that
hopes to enhance all its industries and sectors by treating
knowledge as a key ingredient for success, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the transition to a k-economy must also be placed in
the context of Malaysia's long standing socio-economic obligations.
</P>
<P>
He said the Malaysian government has remained committed to a
growth with equity strategy as it believes that it is imperative
to maintain social justice in its strategic shift towards a k-
economy.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that a k-economy is not merely restricted to
putting the knowledge component into all sectors, but it also
entails the maximum utilization of all productive resources,
especially our human resources," he said.
</P>
<P>
The guiding principles that chart the Malaysian economy in the
next decade must be characterized by the elements such as
competitiveness, innovation, transparency and social equity, he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah, who is also the home minister, also stressed that
even as Malaysia plans for the future, concepts such as peace,
stability and independence will remain crucial, believing "changes
can be made to its economy and society without jeopardizing
stability and peace."
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian Business and Economic Summit organized by the
Asian Strategy and Leadership Institute was themed "Malaysia 2000
and Beyond" and is being attended by senior government officials,
corporate captains and intellectuals.
</P>
<P>
The participants will deliberate on critical issues, challenges
and opportunities on the way towards a knowledge economy,
globalization and regionalization, managing Malaysia's monetary
policy and Malaysia's economic outlook and prospects in the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
They are also scheduled to hold several roundtables with
cabinet ministers, such as on agrifood with the agriculture
minister, on transport and logistic with the transport minister
and on tourism with the culture, arts and tourism minister.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
