<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Hold International Conference on Preventing Blindness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan Ophthalmologists have
organized an international workshop from September 14 to 16 on
preventing blindness in South Asia, the Daily News reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
In addition to eye surgeons from six regional countries, eye
doctors from the United States, the United Kingdom, Australia,
Canada and Switzerland are also due to participate.
</P>
<P>
One of the organizers of the workshop Dr. Upali Mendis said
that the aim of the workshop was to encourage the fighting of
blindness in the region where 15 to 20 million people can get back
their vision with proper eye care and minor surgery.
</P>
<P>
Poverty, ignorance and lack of proper medical care had
prevented blind people from getting their vision back. The
dramatic increase in the age-related eye disease threatens to
overwhelm the region's health care resources and diminish the
quality of life.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that by the year 2030 the number of blind people
would have doubled with macular degradation continuing to be the
leading cause of blindness. It is expected that there would also
be a doubling of the total cases of glaucoma.
</P>
<P>
At the workshop, the eye doctors will exchange notes and ideas
as to how to check blindness in the region and encourage young
doctors to be present.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
