<HEADLINE> Fate of Over 50 Passengers of Missing Indonesian Boat Remains Mystery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The fate of more than 50
passengers on board a wooden boat reported missing on the Malacca
strait on Wednesday remained a mystery while Indonesian and
Malaysian rescuers were still searching for them.
</P>
<P>
"Until the fifth day of the search, the other passengers of the
two countries were still missing," Bengkalis Police Chief
Superintendent Arif Wahyudi was quoted by the Antara News Agency
Monday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, eight survivors of the ill-fated boat were discovered
by Malaysian rescuers, while local fishermen also found two
survivors.
</P>
<P>
The eight survivors were getting medical treatment at a
hospital in Malaysia, while the other two had been sent to the
Bengkalis police station in Riau province.
</P>
<P>
The private television station RCTV reported on Sunday that an
Indonesian warship found 16 dead passengers of the ill-fated boat
which was reportedly carrying around 75 illegal immigrants from a
certain place in Sumatra to Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The wooden boat was reportedly carrying around 75 Indonesian
illegal immigrants from a certain place in Sumatra to unidentified
destination in Malaysia when it capsized in rough sea in the
Malacca strait.
</P>
<P>
However, over 50 passengers and the wreckage of the boat had
not been found, Antara said, adding that hope of finding survivors
and victims grew slim after five days in the sea.
</P>
<P>
The weather over the Malacca strait has been bad in the last
few weeks, as dark clouds had been covering the waters coupled
with strong winds, Antara added. 
</P>
