<HEADLINE> East Timor Leader Cancels Resignation Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- In a dramatic turnaround, East
Timor's independence leader Jose Alexandre Xanana Gusmao and Nobel
peace laureate Jose Ramos-Horta vowed to stay on at the head of
the territory's main political grouping.
</P>
<P>
The vow was made by the two leaders only hours after their
announcement of resignation from the posts as president and co-
vice president of the National Council of Timorese Resistance (
CNRT), an umbrella organization of competing pro-independence
groups.
</P>
<P>
"I will remain, as it is apparently what the people want, and
Xanana, he will stay as well," the Indonesian Observer daily
Monday quoted Ramos-Horta as saying.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the earlier surprise resignation of the two
leaders was due to growing factionalism within the organization.
</P>
<P>
It was unclear whether the two have abandoned plans to stand
for office when East Timor holds its first national elections next
year as part of a UN-supervised transition to full independence.
</P>
<P>
Recently, Xanana quit as head of East Timor 's guerrilla force,
Falintil, which he had led for more than 19 years, on Sunday,
three days before East Timor celebrates its first anniversary of
the August 30 vote in which local people overwhelmingly opted for
independence from Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Xanana, 54, who for close to two decades was East Timor's top
freedom fighter, is believed by many people to become the first
president of East Timor in the forthcoming elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
