<HEADLINE> Car Firms Fuel New Price War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The price war in the Chinese car
market has escalated further with the announcement of new price
cuts by major domestic manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin Xiali Automobile Co. Ltd. slashed the price of two of
its Xiali models by about 8,000 yuan (965 US dollars) on Saturday.
The two models both come with electric fuel injection engines.
</P>
<P>
The FAW (First Automotive Works) Volkswagen Automobile Co. Ltd.
also cut the price of its Jetta model by 12,000 yuan (1,445 US
dollars) last week in Chengdu, capital of southwest China's
Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
The price cuts were aimed at cutting the number of stored cars
and to expand market share, Jia Xinguang, a senior analyst with
the China National Automobile Industry Development and Consulting
Corp., was quoted by today's China Daily as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Price cuts are inevitable as domestic car makers are under
pressure over the country's accession to the World Trade
Organization (WTO)," Jia said.
</P>
<P>
The price cuts are good news for Chinese consumers eager for
mobility, though most of them expect prices to fall still further
after China enters the WTO.
</P>
<P>
China will cut its tariffs on automobile imports from the
current 80 to 100 percent level to 25 percent by mid-2006. The
biggest cuts are expected in the first two years after WTO
accession, which is anticipated to take place at the end of this
year or the beginning of the next.
</P>
<P>
To date, the domestic car market has seen about 15 price cuts
among all brands this year, but the industry still remains in the
doldrums. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
