<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Freshwater Lake Survived Chronic Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Drought-stricken
Baiyangdian, the largest freshwater lake in north China, has
recovered and regained its lush scenery.
</P>
<P>
The lake almost dried up due to years of drought that had
affected most parts of north China. Local government released
water from reservoirs recently to rescue thirsty residents as well
as animals and plants on the banks of the lake.
</P>
<P>
Unexpected rainfall in the mountain areas also contributed to a
raise in the waterline to 6.88 meters, a reasonable level for the
aquatic creatures that inhabit the lake.
</P>
<P>
"The water is very pure now," Zhang Junping, a 62-year-old
fisherman said.
</P>
<P>
China has invested nearly 600 million yuan (about 72.3 million
U.S. dollars) on building up three wastewater treatment plants on
the upper reaches of the lake and closed down over 2,000
enterprises which emit pollutants into the environment.
</P>
<P>
The 500,000-hectare forest and the 20,000 kilometers of
afforestation belt along the banks of the lake also cost 100
million yuan (over 12.4 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Covering a space of over 360 square kilometers, Baiyangdian,
known as "the bright pearl in north China," provides water to
hundreds of thousands of people in Beijing and Tianjin as well as
helps balance the regional ecology.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000828.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
