<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Vows to Kill Budget Deficit by 2004 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The Saudi government said
Monday it would seek, through the 2000-2004 economic and social
development plan, to achieve an annual growth rate of 3.16 percent
and slash the state budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Ministry of Planning said in a statement, which was
released after the cabinet approved the kingdom's seventh
development plan, that the scheme aimed at achieving an annual
growth of the non-oil sector of 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the targeted growth rate would increase non-
oil revenues from last year's 68.4 percent to 71.6 percent of the
gross domestic product (GDP), according to the Saudi Press Agency
monitored here.
</P>
<P>
The state budget deficit will be reduced to zero by 2004,
through non-oil revenues and rationalizing of government spending,
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Budget deficit for fiscal 2000 was projected at 28 billion Saudi
riyals (7.466 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The statement said the new development plan intends to turn the
current account in payment balance from a deficit of 3 percent in
1999 to a surplus of 6.9 percent by the end of 2004.
</P>
<P>
The plan also sought to expand Saudization of manpower in the
oil-rich Gulf kingdom by providing 817,300 jobs.
</P>
<P>
It also stressed the need to develop financial and
administrative structures, and rationalize consumption of economic
resources and energy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
