<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Oman Refinery Co. (ORC) is likely to announce
soon an engineering, procurement and construction (EPC) contract,
worth 750 million U.S. dollars, for a greenfield refinery at Sohar.
</P>
<P>
"It (ORC) is due to award the contract for the 75,000 barrels
per day (bpd) refinery in August," the Middle East Monitor said in
its latest issue.
</P>
<P>
In July, 1998, Idemitsu of Japan was awarded a contract for
management of the company.
</P>
<P>
The ORC is jointly owned by the Ministry of Petroleum and Gas
with 99 percent of its shares and Central Bank of Oman with 1
percent.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Saudi Commerce Ministry has ordered the agents of
Volvo and Mazda to withdraw their defective vehicles from the
market and mend them to ensure the safety of their users.
</P>
<P>
The move followed reports on Volvo's intention to withdraw 116,
000 cars of the model C-80 worldwide due to technical defects in
the driving system, local daily al-Iktisadia quoted on Monday a
statement issued by the ministry as saying.
</P>
<P>
Mazda also said it would withdraw 325 cars of Repute SUV type
due to potential defect in the braking system.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said it had asked the agents of Volvo and Mazda to
speed up the identification of the defective types and withdraw
them from the markets and users and mend them free of charge.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Oman's refinery output rose to 14.23 million
barrels of oil in the first six months of 2000, up by 4.2 percent
from the same period of last year, the Dubai-based Gulf News daily
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of 2000, production of regular fuel rose 12.4
percent to 488,700 barrels and the output of super petrol went up
by 2.1 percent to 1.87 million barrels.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, butane output fell to 162,500 barrels from 189,500
barrels and jet fuel production rose to 755,900 barrels from 690,
000 barrels of the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Oman is planning to build another refinery with a production
capacity of 75,000 barrels a day in 2002 in the northern city of
Sohar.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Oman's crude oil exports rose to 156.5 million
barrels in the first six months of 2000, up by 3.7 percent from
150.9 million barrels in the same period of 1999, the Dubai-based
Gulf News daily reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The figures issued by the Ministry of Commerce and Industry
showed that China is the top importer of Omani crude, accounting
for 32 percent of Oman's total oil exports in the first half of
2000, while Japan came second with 25 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf state, whose economy heavily depends on oil income,
exported 308.8 million barrels of oil last year compared to 301.2
million barrels in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Oman is a medium-sized oil producer which pumps 900,000 barrels
of crude per day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
