<DOCNO> XIE20000828.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strovilia Issue to Test Credibility of U.N. Peacekeepers in Cyprus: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus government spokesman
Michalis Papapetrou Monday noted that the trustworthiness of the
United Nations peacekeeping force in Cyprus (UNFICYP) would be
judged by the Strovilia issue.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing, Papapetrou said that
although the U.N. had made an effort in the right direction on this
issue, the effort was not effective.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities since 1974 when Turkey invaded and occupied the
northern third of the island after a failed coup seeking union with
Greece.
</P>
<P>
The UNFICYP is patrolling the 180-kilometer-long ceasefire line
dividing the two rival sides on this eastern Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
Turkish troops stationed in the Turkish Cypriot area in early
July set up a new checkpoint in Strovilia village in southeastern
Cyprus, changing the military status quo in the area, to retaliate
the U.N. Security Council's renewal of the mandate of UNCIFYP
without asking for their prior approval.
</P>
<P>
The UNFICYP so far failed to persuade the Turkish Cypriot side
to remove the checkpoint and to restore the status quo in the
Strovilia area.
</P>
<P>
Papapetrou also said the Cyprus government considers the visit
by Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash to the village of Strovilia
as an additional provocation. Denktash visited Strovilia on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Papapetrou noted that within the day letters will be sent to U.
N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and the Security Council president,
to protest against the provocative visit.
</P>
<P>
He said the Cyprus government will bring up once again the
demand "for the restoration of the status quo ante in the Strovilia
area.
</P>
<P>
"The government is pushing for the issue to be brought before
the Security Council, to directly take it's responsibilities," he
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
