<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Role of Civic Groups Hailed at U.N. Nongovernmental Organization Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 28 (Xinhua) -- In its efforts to tackle
global problems, the United Nations depends on civic groups, U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 53rd annual conference of the nongovernmental
organizations, Annan pledged to provide nongovernmental
organizations with greater access to the world body.
</P>
<P>
"You are our best defense against complacency, our bravest
campaigners for honesty and our boldest crusaders for change," the
U.N. chief told more than 1,800 representatives who gathered for
the annual conference organized by the U.N. Department of Public
Information.
</P>
<P>
"While ultimately, decisions about the level of nongovernmental
organizations in U.N. work would be taken by the Member States, I
believe that in time, they will agree that our doors must be open,
" Annan said.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general spoke directly to misgivings among some
nongovernmental organizations regarding globalization.
</P>
<P>
"It has been said that arguing against globalization is like
arguing against the law of gravity. But that does not mean we
should accept a law which allows only heavy weights to survive,"
he noted.
</P>
<P>
Annan called on those present to make globalization an engine
that lifts people out of hardship and misery, not a force that
holds them down.
</P>
<P>
Annan said networks bringing together governments, civil
society and the private sector are the most promising partnerships
of our globalizing age, and the task ahead is to move from largely
unplanned interaction towards a more systematic approach to
working together. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
