<HEADLINE> Fire Forces Evacuation of 100 Homes in Montana, U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 28 (Xinhua) -- A new blaze near Yellowstone
National Park has forced the evacuation of 150 homes in Montana
State of the United States, fire officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Officials are concerned that Red Lodge, a town near the
Yellowstone National Park with a population of 1,875, was also
threatened by the fire. The blaze had covered 3,000 acres by
Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
"We're constantly reevaluating whether there will be a need to
evacuate the town," a Forest Service official said.
</P>
<P>
More than 10,000 firefighters are combating 23 wildfires that
have burned some 670,000 acres in the state.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a firestorm in Idaho State destroyed most of the
buildings at a guest ranch, and another guest ranch was ordered
evacuated.
</P>
<P>
Gusty wind in central Idaho Sunday turned one of the blazes
into a firestorm that raced about six miles and burned 21 of the
29 buildings at the Pistol Creek Ranch.
</P>
<P>
No injuries were reported as the area had been evacuated long
before. Fires have blackened about 117,000 acres in Idaho.
</P>
<P>
Fire officials reported a total of more than 1.6 million acres
ablaze in 13 western states in the United States.
</P>
<P>
"It is tragic what's happened out there," Agriculture Secretary
Dan Glickman told Fox News Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
