<HEADLINE> Some UK Train Companies Treble Fares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 28 (Xinhua) - Hidden increases in train fares in
Britain are deterring passengers and undermining government
attempts to cut car use, according to a research paper.
</P>
<P>
The researchers analyzed 2,300 ticket prices and found that the
average rise in fares over the four-year period was 15 percent,
compared with an inflation rate of 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
Rail travel is 40 percent more costly in real terms than 30
years ago, a study for the Rail Passengers' Council shows.
</P>
<P>
The research paper, entitled "Are Passengers Getting Value for
Money?", says someone traveling between London and Liverpool in
1996 paid 35 pounds for a SuperSaver. Now a passenger would pay
140 pounds for the walk-on-Standard Open Return, a 300 percent
increase.
</P>
<P>
Stewart Francis, the council chairman, said there was now less
need for operators to raise the cost of instant travel after the
Government said 60 billion pounds would be invested in rail in the
next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
He said: "Higher fares on many parts of the network are in
danger of undermining the government's attempts to fight
congestion and tackle the social exclusion that occurs when
transport becomes unaffordable for low income groups." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
