<DOCNO> XIE20000828.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Millennium World Peace Summit Opens at U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The Millennium World
Peace Summit Monday kicked off at the U.N. headquarters in New
York, attracting more than 1,000 religious leaders worldwide,
including seven top gurus of China's five major faith disciplines.
</P>
<P>
The religious leaders are gathering here to forge partnerships
of peace with the United Nations and with each other.
</P>
<P>
All the world's major religions and faiths are represented at
the event, "the millennium World Peace Summit of Religious and
Spiritual Leaders," the organizers said.
</P>
<P>
The four-day summit is expected to focus on four broad sets of
issues: conflict transformation, elimination of poverty,
forgiveness and reconciliation, and preservation and restoration
of the environment.
</P>
<P>
The summit brought together recognized religious and spiritual
figures including religious leaders from current zones of conflict
-- such as Sierra Leone, the Balkans, Indonesia, Ethiopia, the
Philippines, Rwanda and the Sudan -- to discuss the roles they can
play in reducing religious tensions, the organizers said.
</P>
<P>
The summit is being convened by an independent group of
interfaith leaders, religious scholars and theologians.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to Bawa Jain, secretary-general of the summit, U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan said, "This gathering of the world's
most pre-eminent religious and spiritual leaders in a united call
for peace will hopefully strengthen the prospect for peace as we
enter the new millennium."
</P>
<P>
"I look forward to the commitment of the religious and
spiritual leaders to the mission of the United Nations, as well as
working together to achieve peace and security in the 21st century,
" Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Annan is expected to speak at the first plenary session of the
summit Tuesday, U.N. officials said here.
</P>
<P>
The president of the 54th U.N. General Assembly, Theo-Ben
Gurirab, is expected to address the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
At the summit, the leaders will discuss how to harness the
power of religious tolerance and spiritual faith to educate and
mobilize their communities to focus on reducing divisions and
ancient antipathies.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting at the U.N. headquarters, these leaders will
continue to engage in the two-day working group sessions at the
Waldorf-Astoria Hotel, in downtown New York City, to devise
special initiatives to address regional conflict, poverty issues,
and environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
Anticipated outcomes of the summit are a Declaration for World
Peace and plans for the establishment of an ongoing International
Advisory Council of Religious and Spiritual Leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000828.0283 </DOCNO>
