<HEADLINE> London Hosts Europe's Biggest Street Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The two-day Notting Hill Carnival,
Europe's largest street festival, ended peacefully Monday in west
London with over 1 million people turning out to watch.
</P>
<P>
Despite a downpour at midday Monday, just as the colorful
parade of floats, flamboyantly dressed dancers and Caribbean steel
bands was about to start, the streets of west London were packed
with spectators ready to party.
</P>
<P>
Police said there had been little trouble given the scale of
the event, with only 18 arrests being made Monday for public order
and drugs offenses and that they were investigating a stabbing
incident.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, the first day of the extravaganza, 57 arrests were
made. More than 7,500 police officers were on duty at the carnival
in an effort to prevent any violence that has marred some previous
festivals.
</P>
<P>
The main celebrations ended at 7:00 p.m. (1800 GMT). All sound
systems were shut down and the floats dispersed although many
private parties continued into the night.
</P>
<P>
The 36th annual Notting Hill Carnival featured more than 75
costume bands and two live stages. During the two-day carnival, at
least 2 million people packed Notting Hill's streets, squares and
bars to sample West Indian food, watch dance troupes and marvel at
a whirl of sights and sounds.
</P>
<P>
The event has its roots in a 1964 street procession aimed at
bringing together an Afro-Caribbean community blighted by racism
and prejudice. It was born among west London's black community in
the 1960s, tracing its roots to the island of Trinidad where the
carnival tradition began as a celebration of the end of slavery.
</P>
<P>
The area won worldwide fame in the blockbuster hit film set in
its streets and starring Hugh Grant and Julia Roberts but has long
been a favorite haunt for Londoners for its street markets and
cafes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
