<HEADLINE> Gore Promotes Prescription Drug Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 28 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Democratic Party
presidential candidate Al Gore promised prescription drugs for all
seniors Monday as he began a week-long focus on health care.
</P>
<P>
Vice President Gore, who campaigned in Florida Monday, told
older voters that his prescription drug plan would help them while
Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush offers only
political ads.
</P>
<P>
"I think the American people deserve to have a full discussion
of all these issues," said Gore, who talked to about 150 senior
citizens invited to share their stories in a round-table at
Florida State University.
</P>
<P>
Gore renewed his criticism of big drug companies for their
lobbying power in Congress and attacked their advertising spending
and their price setting, which makes drugs more expensive.
</P>
<P>
"We need more competition for the big drug companies," Gore
said, hoping to get the support of 39 million seniors covered by
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
Under Gore's proposal, Medicare would pick up all the costs of
prescription drugs for low-income seniors. For the rest, Medicare
would pay half the cost of prescription drugs up to 5,000 dollars
a year.
</P>
<P>
Gore's drug plan would cost 253 billion dollars over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Prescription drugs have become an important election issue as
Americans are living longer. Polls have suggested that voters view
Gore as the candidate most likely to boost the nation's health
care system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
