<HEADLINE> Zanzibar President Inaugurates Free Port Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 29 (Xinhua) -- Zanzibar President Salmin
Amour Tuesday inaugurated the Spice Isles' free port project,
which he said will stimulate business activities and restore the
Isles lost glory as a business center in east and central Africa.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the free port zone with 36,
000 square meters, the president said he is optimistic that the
project will give a fresh impetus to Zanzibar's economic revival
plans in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the free port is a step in the right
direction of carrying out Zanzibar's economic diversification
programs and promoting the transfer of technology so as to ease
the islands' unemployment crisis and improve infrastructure, said
Salmin.
</P>
<P>
"The free port project is part of our struggles in the hope of
giving better life to the people and revamp our economy following
the decline of cloves prices in the world market," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He explained that Zanzibar could become "the second Dubai" when
the project is in full swing, saying many sub-Saharan countries
will import goods from Zanzibar.
</P>
<P>
This measure, Salmin said, will generate a minimum of 84
million U.S. dollars in the initial year.
</P>
<P>
The volume of cargo to be routed through the Zanzibar port will
rise to about 30,380 cargo containers per year, up from less than
7,300 at present, he added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, director general of the Isles Free Port Authority
Ahmed Sheikh announced they plan to spend about 2.3 billion
Tanzanian shillings (about 2.9 million U.S. dollars) to provide
facilities for the port.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that a total of 13 sheds with 800 square meters
each will be built in the zone plus an administration block which
will house offices to provide several services for the free port.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar joined with mainland Tanganyika to form the United
Republic of Tanzania in 1964. But it has its own government and
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Cloves are the main export of Zanzibar, providing about 80
percent of the islands' foreign-exchange earnings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
