<HEADLINE> Congolese FM Demands to Amend Lusaka Peace Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 29 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Affairs Minister of the
Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) Abdoulaye Yerodia Tuesday
demanded to immediately amend the "obsolete" Lusaka peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters after meeting Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe that the peace agreement has failed to speed up the peace
process in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
"The Lusaka peace agreement is still on track, but is not on a
very fast train," he said. "We want it to go faster than it is now,
but it cannot because it has been overtaken by events."
</P>
<P>
He said the peace agreement should be amended to recognize
Uganda and Rwanda as aggressors in the DRC and not as parties to
the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
"If we follow the Lusaka peace agreement, it will be used by
our oppressors to prolong their stay in our country," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said there is no way for the DRC to accept former Botswana
President Ketumile Masire as a mediator to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Masire was appointed the peace facilitator in the DRC by the
Organization of African Unity, but the DRC government rejected him,
accusing him of being biased.
</P>
<P>
In response, Zimbabwe's Foreign Affairs Minister Stan Mudenge
said the Lusaka peace agreement could be amended according to the
demands of the DRC government.
</P>
<P>
"The peace agreement can be amended because we have already
done that at some time," Mudenge said, adding "it is not written
on stone that it cannot be amended."
</P>
<P>
The Lusaka peace agreement was signed by all belligerents in
the DRC in July and August last year to pave way for the
deployment of U.N. peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia had been fighting on the side of
DRC President Laurent Kabila to push out rebels supported by
Rwanda and Uganda in the two-year old civil war erupted in 1998.
</P>
<P>
At least three countries have reportedly offered to send troops
to the DRC under the U.N. peacekeeping mission. These include
Pakistan, Senegal and Morocco.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, Ukraine and Nigeria have agreed to provide
logistical support to the peace mission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
