<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Police Warned Against Violating Human Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 29 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean police were warned
Tuesday against violating human rights while conducting business,
the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Human rights violations have tarnished the image of the
organization and antagonized the police force with the community
they are mandated to serve, Zimbabwean police chief staff officer
responsible for human resources at the Harare headquarters Senior
Assistant Commissioner Shepherd Gwasira was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He told a human rights workshop for 30 superintendents and
chief superintendents from all stations in the country that "if
police officers violate human rights, then they turn out to be the
law breakers."
</P>
<P>
The five-day workshop, organized by the Zimbabwe Republic
Police in conjunction with the Human Rights Research and
Documentation Trust of Southern Africa, is aimed at helping police
officers to observe human rights when doing their work.
</P>
<P>
"It is our intention to ensure that all police commanders
receive training in human rights, gender and law to guard against
any form of violating the law," Gwasira said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the police to portray a good image of the country
internationally by adhering to ethical and legal conduct expected
of law enforcement officials. 
