<HEADLINE> Africa Governance Forum to Be Held in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 29 (Xinhua) -- Representatives from 16 sub-
Saharan African countries will discuss issues vital to the
continent's future at the fourth Africa Governance Forum in Uganda
's capital Kampala from September 1 to 3.
</P>
<P>
The forum, organized by the United Nations Development Program
(UNDP) and the Office of Prime Minister of Uganda, will focus on
the contribution of the parliamentary process in strengthening
governance in Africa, according to a UNDP press release on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Highlighting the importance of the forum, UNDP Administrator
Mark Malloch Brown said "ineffective governance often short-
circuits the connection between anti-poverty efforts and poverty
reduction, that is why good governance built around strong,
transparent and democratic institutions is so important."
</P>
<P>
The Africa Governance Forum provides a platform for Africans,
international organizations and Africa's external development
partners to engage in dialogue on the state of governance in the
continent.
</P>
<P>
The third forum was held last year in Mali and deliberated on
conflict management and governance.
</P>
<P>
Ghana hosted the second on "accountability and transparency in
Africa" while the inaugural one was held in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia,
to address issues of leadership building, strengthening
parliamentary, judicial and administrative systems and peace and
stability as well as free and responsible press. 
</P>
</TEXT>
