<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At Least 26 Killed in Somali Clan Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 29 (Xinhua) -- At least 26 people were killed
and more than 20 others wounded in three separate armed
confrontations in the past two days in Jowhar town, 90 kilometers
north of Mogadishu, Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The first confrontation started when rival militiamen from the
Hawadleh and Galje'el clans exchanged heavy gunfire near the main
market of the town. Eyewitnesses said the Galje'el clansmen lost
12 of their fighters while their Hawadleh opponents lost eight
during a fighting right inside the market place.
</P>
<P>
Four innocent civilians were killed in a nearby house after a
stray round of assault grenade landed inside it. Six others were
wounded in the ablaze.
</P>
<P>
The shooting subsided a little after the Galje'el clan
militiamen withdrew from the town leaving their houses and
properties under the mercy of their friendly and strong Warsangeli
subclan of Abgal to protect.
</P>
<P>
As the Hawadleh clan militiamen went around the area in search
of something to loot, they met a man with a gun guarding an oil-
milling machine. In blunder they killed the man who happened to be
a Warsangeli fighter.
</P>
<P>
The Warsangeli militiamen, annoyed by the killing, attacked the
Hawadleh militiamen in their turn. The ensuing exchange of heavy
fire forced the Hawadleh clan militiamen to withdraw from the town
to Buraneh village, about 23 kilometers north of the town on
Monday, thus giving chance for the return of the ousted Galje'el
militiamen.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, another armed confrontation has begun between the
Warsangeli and Agon-Yar subclans of Abgal dominating the entire
region. At least two men were killed, one from each side, and four
others wounded as the two sides exchanged gunfire at the entrance
of the town.
</P>
<P>
The wounded include a well-known businessman, Ahmed Hassan, who
sustained gunshot wounds as he tried to curb down the hostility.
</P>
<P>
Jowhar town is calm Tuesday, with talks now continuing between
the two Abgal subclans of Warsangeli and Agon-Yar. But no talks
has been initiated between Hawadleh and Galje'el nor Hawadleh and
Warsangeli.
</P>
<P>
In another development, faction leaders of Mogadishu who
boycott the Djibouti-sponsored Somali peace conference have
started making political journeys by rushing outside the country
one after the other.
</P>
<P>
Osman Ali Atto left for Nairobi Monday over what is called
consultations aimed at searching political solution to Somalia's
problems, his aides said.
</P>
<P>
His move was followed by Hussein Mohamed Aidid and Hussein
Hajji Bod, who left for Sanaa of Yemen on Tuesday. According to
their close deputies, the two faction leaders have received
official invitation from President Ali Abdalle Salah of Yemen.
</P>
<P>
Salah, who witnessed the recent inauguration ceremony of Somali
President Abdiqasim Salad Hassan, has been among the front runners
of the regional presidents supporting the Djibouti peace
conference.
</P>
<P>
Atto and Mohamed Qanyare Afrah, another faction leader, are
reportedly departing from Nairobi for Sanaa to join their fellow
faction leaders already there on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The unexpected departure of the faction leaders from Mogadishu
is seen as another new tentative in which President Salah is
trying to persuade them to join the government to be established
in Djibouti soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
