<HEADLINE> Kenya Sets Up Fishery Authority </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 29 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
established an authority to oversee the operations of the fishing
industry, media reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The move is the government's latest initiative to fulfill the
European Union (EU) requirements set in 1998 when the EU banned
the fish export from Kenya due to hygienic reasons.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Minister for Rural Development Maalim Mohammed said here
Monday that the authority headed by Agriculture Permanent
Secretary Shem Migot Adhola would oversee implementation of
regulations governing fish-processing, handling and transportation
to both local and export markets.
</P>
<P>
The functions of the authority include monitoring fishing
grounds, controlling fish landing, approving establishment of fish
processing factories as well as issuing health compliance
certificates, Mohammed said.
</P>
<P>
The ban by the EU has been a severe setback to Kenya's fishing
industry which nets more than 6.5 billion shillings (about 84.4
million U.S. dollars) and employs over 40,000 fishermen annually.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed expressed optimism that the ban would be lifted by the
EU since the Kenyan government and other stake holders had met all
the conditions set by the EU.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
