<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Launches Anti-Poaching Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 29 (Xinhua) -- The Zambia Wildlife Authority (
ZAWA) has successfully launched an anti-poaching campaign
arresting more than 700 poachers and confiscating about 239
firearms throughout the country in the first seven months of this
year, Times of Zambia newspaper reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It quoted Henry Mwima, ZAWA director of operations and research,
as saying in Lusaka on Monday that also seized were 63 ivory and
430 rounds of assorted ammunition.
</P>
<P>
The transformation of the department of national parks and
wildlife services(NPWS) into ZAWA late last year, had created a
big vacuum with a lot of field officers being pulled out from the
national parks, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Mwima said the wildlife officers who have had their contracts
renewed have been instructed to move into the field as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
He said the poachers had taken advantage of the operational
changes that ZAWA had instituted and were roaming the parks at
will.
</P>
<P>
"Now that we have deployed our men into the field, the poaching
rate in the national parks will reduce tremendously," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said last week more than 10 poachers were arrested and 14
pieces of ivory confiscated by wildlife police officers from the
Kafue National Park.
</P>
<P>
Mwima said the wildlife officers deployed in the field have
been provided with all the necessary resources to enable them
fight poachers.
</P>
<P>
He said ZAWA was committed to providing logistical support,
uniforms and equipment in order to strengthen field operations of
their officers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
