<HEADLINE> Zambia Asks Congolese Rebels to Release Fishermen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 29 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has made
contact with the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) rebels on
the release of the 26 Zambian fishermen in custody, Home Affairs
Minister Peter Machungwa has said.
</P>
<P>
Briefing the press in Lusaka on Monday, the minister said the
rebels were demanding ransom before they could releasee the
Zambians.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's Times of Zambia newspaper quoted the minister as
saying the rebels however did not give the amount they wanted.
</P>
<P>
He said further investigation was being made to establish what
happened exactly.
</P>
<P>
"It could be that the rebels are asking for a fee, like
immigration, or probably for fishing on foreign waters because
these people were blown to the DRC side by the winds," the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
He said the men were fishing between Nsumbu bay and Lake
Tanganyika last Saturday when they were blown by the wind.
</P>
</TEXT>
