<HEADLINE> Canada, Brazil to Negotiate Solution on Aircraft Subsidy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Canadian and Brazilian
negotiators are scheduled to meet for the fourth time in Sao Paulo
this week on Brazil's Proex aircraft subsidy program, the Canadian
government announced here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Canada's priority remains reaching a mutually satisfactory
negotiated resolution with Brazil on this issue," said Canadian
International Trade Minister Pierre Pettigrew in the announcement.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, the World Trade Organization (WTO)
arbitration panel ruled in Geneva that Canada can apply 344
million U.S. dollars per year in countermeasures against Brazil
for the subsidy issue.
</P>
<P>
Pettigrew described the latest WTO arbitration as the "fifth
consecutive ruling against Brazil," saying that "the WTO agrees
with Canada that the Proex subsidy should be withdrawn as soon as
possible."
</P>
<P>
Four previous WTO panels have also ruled that Brazil's Proex
export subsidy for regional aircraft violates that country's WTO
obligations and must be withdrawn, according to Canadian
government sources.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Canadian Industry Minister John Manley expressed
support for negotiation with Brazil.
</P>
<P>
"Resolving this dispute will promote increased trade between
Canada and Brazil to the benefit of both countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
Canada has yet to require for authority to impose
countermeasures from the Dispute Settlement Body of the WTO if it
really decides to take retaliation under the WTO ruling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
