<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Slams Denktash for Negatively Affecting Cyprus Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Denktash does everything he can to affect the Cyprus talks in
a negative way," said Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas
at a press briefing Monday.
</P>
<P>
Complaining that the U.N. did not undertake any initiatives
with regard to Denktash's actions, Reppas said that the
international organization must take action with regard to the
continuous provocations of Denktash.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriots-controlled
south and the Turkish Cypriots-dominated north since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
eastern Mediterranean island in the wake of a failed coup seeking
union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Denktash and Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides have held
several rounds of indirect talks in New York and Geneva, but these
talks have failed to make some breakthroughs in seeking a fair and
just solution to the protracted Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The Greek-Cypriot side hopes that the next round of talks will
be a direct one and can become substantive.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus Foreign Minister Ioannis Kasoulides is to arrive in
Athens Tuesday to have talks with his Greek counterpart, George
Papandreou, in order to coordinate their actions for substantive
talks between the two communities in Cyprus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
