<HEADLINE> British Foreign Office Minister to Visit Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 28 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Office Minister
Peter Hain is scheduled to visit Israel and the Palestinian
Authority Tuesday to offer encouragement for the Middle East peace
process, it was announced here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The purpose of my visit is to use Britain's influence and
friendships in the region to encourage progress, not to broker a
deal or seek a breakthrough," Hain said in a statement issued by
the Foreign Office.
</P>
<P>
"The window of opportunity for agreement is small. Now is the
time for friends of the peace process to do what they can to
encourage all the parties to work as constructively as possible
while there is still time," said Hain.
</P>
<P>
Hain's Mideast tour coincides with a trip to London by Israel's
acting Foreign Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami, who is due to meet British
Foreign Secretary Robin Cook.
</P>
<P>
Ben-Ami, currently visiting several European countries to seek
support for Israel's stand in the peace process, has said an
accord with the Palestinians is within reach and both sides must
grasp it.
</P>
<P>
"We are on the verge of being able to reach a final agreement (
with Palestinians)," Ben-Ami reportedly said in an interview to
the French daily Le Monde.
</P>
<P>
The key issues of Jerusalem and the fate of Palestinian
refugees were believed to be behind the failure of last month's
peace summit at Camp David in the United States.  
</P>
</TEXT>
