<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Considers Report of Sierra Leone Captors' Demand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 28 (Xinhua) -- British officials trying to win
the release of the 11 British soldiers captured in Sierra Leone
said Sunday that they were investigating a report from the West
African country that rebel captors were demanding freedom for one
of their jailed leaders in exchange for the soldiers' release.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Ministry said it was looking into an unconfirmed
report that a group called the West Side Boys said it would
release the Britons in exchange for a fighter known as General
Papa, who was arrested in June after a fight with United Nations
peacekeepers over the ownership of a vehicle.
</P>
<P>
The captors reportedly also want their supplies replenished
before the British soldiers are released.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Defense Ministry said a team of "varying makeup"
had been sent to help secure the release of the men and they would
consider any possible resolution.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident we can secure their release through
discussion with their captors, and the team was sent in order to
aid that process," local reports here quoted a spokesman in the
Ministry of Defense as saying.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, British officials said the leader of the 11-man
British team, which was captured Friday while patrolling near
Freetown, capital of Sierra Leone, had been in contact and said
all were "being fed and well-treated."
</P>
<P>
"We have made contact with those who appear to be holding," a
Defense Ministry spokesman said Sunday, adding that "discussions
are at a very early stage."
</P>
<P>
He also said that Britain was "working closely with the
government of Sierra Leone to try to bring this to a conclusion."
</P>
<P>
Reports from Freetown said a British force spokesman had said
he could not confirm or deny the reported demands of the abductors.
</P>
<P>
"All I can say for certain is efforts are continuing to secure
their speedy release," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the 11 soldiers lost contact with their base, where
British instructors are training Sierra Leonean army recruits.
They were accompanied by a government soldier, who was acting as
their guide and was also believed to have been captured.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leone had been a colony of Britain. A civil war broke
out there in 1991 and the United States had to send in a peace-
keeping force.
</P>
<P>
Britain sent 1,000 soldiers to Freetown when the rebels re-
started the conflict in May. The rebels seized 500 U.N.
peacekeepers and advanced toward the capital. When the British
forces withdrew in mid-June, they left behind 400 soldiers to
train Sierra Leone army recruits. Britain has also donated arms
and equipment and sent military advisers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
