<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Calls for Implementation of Cease-fire Agreement in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 29 (Xinhua) -- Visiting United Nations Under-
Secretary Ibrahim Gambari has called for a quick implementation of
Lusaka ceasefire agreement signed last year to solve conflict in
the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Gambari, also special advisor to the U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan, said the U.N. Security Council is waiting for the
implementation of the agreement in the DRC so as to work on
sending 5,500 U.N. peacekeepers to the country.
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing here on Tuesday, Gambari said: "We hope the
Congolese government and the rebels will come to the agreement
soon for the U.N. to decide on the deployment of the troops as
long as the conditions have been improved in that country."
</P>
<P>
Shortly before his departure for Namibia, Gambari said the
purpose of his visit to Zambia was to see the situation on the
Angola and Namibia border areas.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the situation in refugee camps in Western
Province in terms of medical equipment was good while some
infrastructures needed to be improved.
</P>
<P>
Zambia was faced with the challenge of accommodating a growing
number of refugees from Angola and the DRC, he said.
</P>
<P>
There are at present over 230,000 refugees in Zambia, 160,000
of which are from Angola.
</P>
<P>
Gambari said his mission has been accomplished by visiting some
refugee camps and having discussions with Zambian President
Frederick Chiluba and government officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
